#: static/faq.html:508
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS uses an enhanced version of the modern filesystem-based disk\n"
"                    encryption implementation in the Android Open Source Project. The officially\n"
"                    supported devices have substantial hardware-based support for enhancing the\n"
"                    security of the encryption implementation. GrapheneOS has full support for the\n"
"                    hardware-based encryption features just as it does with other hardware-based\n"
"                    security features."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:514
msgid ""
"Firmware and OS partitions are identical copies of the images published in\n"
"                    the official releases. The authenticity and integrity of these partitions is\n"
"                    verified from a root of trust on every boot. No data is read from any of these\n"
"                    images without being cryptographically verified. Encryption is out of scope\n"
"                    due to the images being publicly available. Verified boot offers much stronger\n"
"                    security properties than disk encryption. Further details will be provided in\n"
"                    another section on verified boot in the future."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:521
msgid ""
"The data partition stores all of the persistent state for the operating\n"
"                    system. Full disk encryption is implemented via filesystem-based encryption\n"
"                    with metadata encryption. All data, file names and other metadata is always\n"
"                    stored encrypted. This is often referred to as file-based encryption but it\n"
"                    makes more sense to call it filesystem-based encryption. It's implemented by\n"
"                    the Linux kernel as part of the ext4 and f2fs implementation rather than running\n"
"                    a block-based encryption layer. The advantage of filesystem-based encryption\n"
"                    is the ability to use fine-grained keys rather than a single global key that's\n"
"                    always in memory once the device is booted."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:530
msgid ""
"Disk encryption keys are randomly generated with a high quality CSPRNG and\n"
"                    stored encrypted with a key encryption key. Key encryption keys are derived at\n"
"                    runtime and are never stored anywhere."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:533
msgid ""
"Sensitive data is stored in user profiles. User profiles each have their\n"
"                    own unique, randomly generated disk encryption key and their own unique key\n"
"                    encryption key is used to encrypt it. The owner profile is special and is used\n"
"                    to store sensitive system-wide operating system data. This is why the owner\n"
"                    profile needs to be logged in after a reboot before other user profiles can be\n"
"                    used. The owner profile does not have access to the data in other profiles.\n"
"                    Filesystem-based encryption is designed so that files can be deleted without\n"
"                    having the keys for their data and file names, which enables the owner profile\n"
"                    to delete other profiles without them being active."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:542
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS enables support for ending secondary user profile sessions after\n"
"                    logging into them. It adds an end session button to the lockscreen and in the\n"
"                    global action menu accessed by holding the power button. This fully purges the\n"
"                    encryption keys and puts the profiles back at rest. This can't be done for the\n"
"                    owner profile without rebooting due to it encrypting the sensitive system-wide\n"
"                    operating system data."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:548
msgid ""
"Using a secondary profile for regular usage allows you to make use of the\n"
"                    device without decrypting the data in your regular usage profile. It also\n"
"                    allows putting it at rest without rebooting the device. Even if you use the\n"
"                    same passphrase for multiple profiles, each of those profiles still ends up\n"
"                    with a unique key encryption key and a compromise of the OS while one of them\n"
"                    is active won't leak the passphrase. The advantage to using separate\n"
"                    passphrases is in case an attacker records you entering it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:555
msgid ""
"File data is encrypted with AES-256-XTS and file names with AES-256-CTS. A\n"
"                    unique key is derived using HKDF-SHA512 for each regular file, directory and\n"
"                    symbolic link from the per-profile encryption keys, or the global encryption\n"
"                    key for non-sensitive data stored outside of profiles. The directory key is\n"
"                    used to encrypt the file names. GrapheneOS increases the file name padding\n"
"                    from 16 bytes to 32 bytes. AES-256-XTS with the global encryption key is also\n"
"                    used to encrypt filesystem metadata as a whole beyond the finer-grained file\n"
"                    name encryption."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:563
msgid ""
"The OS derives a password token from the profile's lock method credential\n"
"                    using scrypt. This is used as the main input for key derivation."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:565
msgid ""
"The OS stores a high entropy random value as the Weaver token on the secure\n"
"                    element (Titan M on Pixels) and uses it as another input for key derivation.\n"
"                    The Weaver token is stored alongside a Weaver key derived by the OS from the\n"
"                    password token. In order to retrieve the Weaver token, the secure element\n"
"                    requires the correct Weaver key. A secure internal timer is used to implement\n"
"                    hardware-based delays for each attempt at key derivation. It quickly ramps up\n"
"                    to 1 day delays before the next attempt. Weaver also provides reliable wiping\n"
"                    of data since the secure element can reliably wipe a Weaver slot. Deleting a\n"
"                    profile will wipe the corresponding Weaver slot and a factory reset of the\n"
"                    device wipes all of the Weaver slots. The secure element also provides insider\n"
"                    attack resistance preventing firmware updates before authenticating with the\n"
"                    owner profile."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:577
msgid ""
"Standard delays for encryption key derivation enforced by the secure\n"
"                    element:"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:580
msgid "0 to 4 failed attempts: no delay"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:581
msgid "5 failed attempts: 30 second delay"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:582
msgid "6 to 9 failed attempts: no delay"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:583
msgid "10 to 29 failed attempts: 30 second delay"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:584
msgid "30 to 139 failed attempts: 30 × 2"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:584
msgid "⌊("
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:584 static/faq.html:585
msgid "n"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:584
msgid " - 30) ÷ 10⌋"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:584
msgid ""
"\n"
"                        where "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:585
msgid ""
" is the number of failed attempts. This means the delay\n"
"                        doubles after every 10 attempts. There's a 30 second delay after 30 failed\n"
"                        attempts, 60s after 40, 120s after 50, 240s after 60, 480s after 70, 960s\n"
"                        after 80, 1920s after 90, 3840s after 100, 7680s after 110, 15360s after\n"
"                        120 and 30720s after 130"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:590
msgid "140 or more failed attempts: 86400 second delay (1 day)"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:592
msgid ""
"Invalid input outside the minimum or maximum length limits of the UI won't\n"
"                    trigger an attempt at authentication or key derivation."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:594
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS only officially supports devices with Weaver. The fallback\n"
"                    implementation for devices without it is out-of-scope for this FAQ."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:596
msgid ""
"The password token, Weaver token and other values like the OS verified boot\n"
"                    key are used by the TEE as inputs to a hardware-bound key derivation algorithm\n"
"                    provided by the SoC. The general concept is having the SoC perform hardware\n"
"                    accelerated key derivation using an algorithm like AES or HMAC keyed with a\n"
"                    hard-wired hardware key inaccessible to software or firmware. This is meant to\n"
"                    prevent offloading a brute force attack onto more powerful hardware without an\n"
"                    expensive process of extracting the hardware key from the SoC."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:603
msgid ""
"Many apps use the hardware keystore, their own encryption implementation or\n"
"                    a combination of those to provide an additional layer of encryption. As an\n"
"                    example, an app can use the hardware keystore to encrypt their data with a key\n"
"                    only available when the device is unlocked to keep their data at rest when the\n"
"                    profile is locked but not logged out. This is beyond the scope of this FAQ\n"
"                    section."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:611
msgid ""
"Can apps spy on the clipboard in the background or inject content into it?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:612
msgid ""
"As of Android 10, only the configured default input method editor (your\n"
"                    keyboard of choice) and the currently focused app can read the clipboard\n"
"                    content. Apps without focus cannot read the clipboard. This is a stricter\n"
"                    restriction than preventing apps in the background from reading it, since an\n"
"                    app in the foreground or a foreground service cannot read it, only the\n"
"                    foreground app that's currently focused. Clipboard managers need to be\n"
"                    implemented by the keyboard chosen as the default by the user."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:619
msgid "Both background and foreground apps can write data to the clipboard."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:620
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS previously restricted background clipboard access as a much earlier and\n"
"                    slightly less strict implementation of this feature. It provided a toggle for users to\n"
"                    whitelist clipboard managers, which is no longer needed now that keyboards are\n"
"                    expected to provide it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:624
msgid ""
"As of Android 12, the user is notified when an app reads clipboard content\n"
"                    which was set by a different app. This notice is enabled by default and can be\n"
"                    toggled under "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:626
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    Security &amp; privacy &gt; Privacy controls &gt; Show clipboard access"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:630
msgid "Can apps access hardware identifiers?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:631
msgid ""
"As of Android 10, apps cannot obtain permission to access non-resettable hardware\n"
"                    identifiers such as the serial number, MAC addresses, IMEIs/MEIDs, SIM card serial\n"
"                    numbers and subscriber IDs. Only privileged apps included in the base system with\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:634
msgid ""
" whitelisted can access these hardware\n"
"                    identifiers. Apps targeting Android 10 will receive a\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:636
msgid ""
" and older apps will receive an empty value for\n"
"                    compatibility. The currently enabled carrier-based messaging app for SMS/MMS/RCS\n"
"                    is a special case that's given access to certain device identifiers including\n"
"                    the IMEI. This is normally the GrapheneOS fork of AOSP Messaging but can be\n"
"                    changed to another app by the user."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:641
msgid ""
"Since these restrictions became standard, GrapheneOS only makes a small change to\n"
"                    remove a legacy form of access to the serial number by legacy apps, which was still\n"
"                    around for compatibility. It used to need more extensive changes such as disallowing\n"
"                    access to the serial number but those restrictions are now standard."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:645
msgid ""
"Apps can determine the model of the device (such as it being a Pixel 6) either\n"
"                    directly or indirectly through the properties of the hardware and software. There\n"
"                    isn't a way to avoid this short of the OS supporting running apps in a virtual machine\n"
"                    with limited functionality and hardware acceleration. Hiding the CPU/SoC model would\n"
"                    require not even using basic hardware virtualization support and these things could\n"
"                    probably still be detected via performance measurements."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:654
msgid ""
"In addition to not having a way to identify the hardware, apps cannot directly\n"
"                    identify the installation of the OS on the hardware. Apps only have a small portion of\n"
"                    the OS configuration exposed to them and there is not much for device owners to change\n"
"                    which could identify their installation. Apps can detect that they're being run on\n"
"                    GrapheneOS via the privacy and security features placing further restrictions on them\n"
"                    and hardening them against further exploitation. Apps can identify their own app\n"
"                    installation via their app data and can directly (until that's removed) or indirectly\n"
"                    identify a profile. Profiles should be used when separate identities are desired.\n"
"                    Profiles can be used as temporary ephemeral identities by creating them for a specific\n"
"                    need and then deleting them. The rest of this answer only provides more technical\n"
"                    details, so you can stop reading here if you only want an overview and actionable\n"
"                    advice (i.e. use profiles as identities not inherently tied to each other)."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:666
msgid ""
"Examples of the global OS configuration available to apps are time zone,\n"
"                    network country code and other similar global settings. Per-profile examples\n"
"                    are dark mode and language. Similar to extension and browser configuration and\n"
"                    state being fingerprinted by web sites, an app could use a combination of\n"
"                    these things in an attempt to identify the installation. All of these things\n"
"                    vary at runtime and can be changed, but some are fairly unlikely to change in\n"
"                    practice after the initial setup of the device such as the ones listed above.\n"
"                    GrapheneOS will likely add further restrictions in this area and a couple\n"
"                    toggles for certain cases like time zones to use a standard value instead."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:675
msgid ""
"Apps can generate their own 128-bit or larger random value and use that as an\n"
"                    identifier for the app installation. Apps can create data in their app-specific\n"
"                    external storage directory by default without needing permission, and in the legacy\n"
"                    storage model before API 29 that data persists after the app is uninstalled, so it can\n"
"                    be used to store an ID that persists through the app being uninstalled and\n"
"                    reinstalled. However, external storage is under control of the user and the user can\n"
"                    delete this data at any time, including after uninstalling the app. In the modern\n"
"                    storage model, this data is automatically removed when the app is uninstalled.\n"
"                    GrapheneOS includes Seedvault as an OS backup service which must be explicitly\n"
"                    enabled, and it has the option to automatically restore app data when an app is\n"
"                    reinstalled, so it wouldn't lose track of it being the same profile."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:686 static/faq.html:697 static/faq.html:699
#: static/faq.html:703 static/faq.html:714
msgid "ANDROID_ID"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:686
msgid ""
" string is a 64-bit random number, unique to each\n"
"                    combination of profile and app signing key. The 64-bit limitation means it isn't\n"
"                    particularly useful due to the possibility of collisions. It's tied to the lifetime of\n"
"                    profiles and does not persist through profile deletion or a factory reset. This is\n"
"                    comparable to an app targeting the legacy storage model storing a 64-bit random value\n"
"                    in the app-specific external storage directory. In the future, GrapheneOS will likely\n"
"                    change this to be tied to the lifetime of app installations rather than profiles. An\n"
"                    app could still track the identity of the profile through data you give it access to or\n"
"                    via data another app chooses to share with them."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:695
msgid ""
"The advertising ID is a Google Play services feature not included in the baseline\n"
"                    Android API, so it isn't an API included in GrapheneOS. The advertising ID is unique\n"
"                    to each profile. It isn't unique to each app signing key like "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:697
msgid ""
",\n"
"                    but that makes little difference since apps within the same profile can communicate\n"
"                    with each other with mutual consent. It's comparable to "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:699
msgid ""
" but\n"
"                    provides an 128-bit value so it provides a strong cryptographic guarantee against\n"
"                    collisions, although a device messing with apps could set it to the same value used in\n"
"                    another profile. The advertising ID is exposed via the Settings app and can be reset\n"
"                    to a new random value, unlike "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:703
msgid ""
" which remains the same for the\n"
"                    lifetime of the profile, but apps can tie it to the previous ID since they can detect\n"
"                    that it changed via their own ID in their app data. The advertising ID can\n"
"                    also now be disabled (zeroed)."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:707
msgid ""
"Apps do not have access to user data by default and cannot ever access the data of\n"
"                    other apps without those apps going out of the way to share it with them. If apps are\n"
"                    granted read access to user data like media or contacts, they could use it to identify\n"
"                    the profile. If apps are granted write access to user data, they could tag it to keep\n"
"                    track of the profile. Apps previously had little reason to do things like this because\n"
"                    they were able to persist data through an uninstall and reinstallation by default. The\n"
"                    modern storage model means they need to request access to user data to do this. The\n"
"                    existence of "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:714
msgid ""
" means they don't yet need to bother with that but\n"
"                    that will change on GrapheneOS and will likely change for baseline Android too.\n"
"                    However, profiles are the only way to provide a strong assurance of separate\n"
"                    identities since the application model of the OS is designed to support communication\n"
"                    between apps within the same profile, but never between them."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:721
msgid ""
"What does GrapheneOS do about cellular tracking, interception and silent "
"SMS?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:722
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS always considers networks to be hostile and avoids placing trust in\n"
"                    them. It leaves out various carrier apps included in the stock OS granting carriers\n"
"                    varying levels of administrative access beyond standard carrier configuration.\n"
"                    GrapheneOS also avoids trust in the cellular network in other ways including providing\n"
"                    a secure network time update implementation rather than trusting the cellular network\n"
"                    for this. Time is sensitive and can be used to bypass security checks depending on\n"
"                    certificate and key expiry."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:729
msgid ""
"Cellular networks use inherently insecure protocols and have many trusted parties.\n"
"                    Even if interception of the connection or some other man-in-the-middle attack along\n"
"                    the network is not currently occurring, the network is still untrustworthy and\n"
"                    information should not be sent unencrypted."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:733
msgid ""
"Authenticated transport encryption such as HTTPS for web sites avoids trusting the\n"
"                    cellular network. End-to-end encrypted protocols such as the Signal messaging protocol\n"
"                    also avoid trusting the servers. GrapheneOS uses authenticated encryption with modern\n"
"                    protocols, forward secrecy and strong cipher configurations for our services. We only\n"
"                    recommend apps taking a decent approach in this area."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:738
msgid ""
"Legacy calls and texts should be avoided as they're not secure and trust the\n"
"                    carrier and network along with having weak security against other parties. Trying to\n"
"                    detect some forms of interception rather than dealing with the root of the problem\n"
"                    (unencrypted communications and unencrypted data transfer) would be foolish and doomed to\n"
"                    failure."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:743
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS does not add gimmicks without a proper threat model and\n"
"                    rationale. We won't include flawed heuristics to guess when the cellular\n"
"                    network should be trusted. These kinds of features provide a false sense of\n"
"                    security and encourage unwarranted trust in cellular protocols and carrier\n"
"                    networks as the default. These also trigger false positives causing\n"
"                    unnecessary concern and panic. The correct approach is avoiding trusting the\n"
"                    network as explained above."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:750
msgid ""
"Connecting to your carrier's network inherently depends on you identifying yourself to\n"
"                    it and anyone able to obtain administrative access. Activating airplane mode will\n"
"                    fully disable the cellular radio transmit and receive capabilities, which will prevent\n"
"                    your phone from being reached from the cellular network and stop your carrier (and\n"
"                    anyone impersonating them to you) from tracking the device via the cellular radio. The\n"
"                    baseband implements other functionality such as Wi-Fi and GPS functionality, but each\n"
"                    of these components is separately sandboxed on the baseband and independent of each\n"
"                    other. Enabling airplane mode disables the cellular radio, but Wi-Fi can be re-enabled\n"
"                    and used without activating the cellular radio again. This allows using the device as\n"
"                    a Wi-Fi only device."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:760
msgid ""
"LTE-only mode added by GrapheneOS is solely\n"
"                    intended for attack surface reduction"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:761
msgid ""
". It should not be mistaken as a way to make\n"
"                    the cellular network into something that can be trusted."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:763
msgid ""
"Receiving a silent SMS is not a good indicator of being targeted by your cell\n"
"                    carrier, police or government because "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:764
msgid ""
"anyone on the cell network can send\n"
"                    them"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:765
msgid ""
" including yourself. Cellular triangulation will happen regardless of whether\n"
"                    or not SMS texts are being sent or received by the phone. Even if an SMS did serve a\n"
"                    useful purpose for tracking, a silent SMS would be little different than receiving\n"
"                    unsolicited spam. In fact, sending spam would be stealthier since it wouldn't trigger\n"
"                    alerts for silent SMS but rather would be ignored with the rest of the spam. Regardless,\n"
"                    sending texts or other data is not required or particularly useful to track devices\n"
"                    connected to a network for an adversary with the appropriate access."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:772
msgid ""
"Airplane mode is the only way to avoid the cellular network tracking your\n"
"                    device and works correctly on the devices we support."
msgstr ""

