"                            downloaded from\n"
"                            https://broadcom.psds.grapheneos.org/lto2.dat,\n"
"                            https://broadcom.psds.grapheneos.org/rto.dat and\n"
"                            https://broadcom.psds.grapheneos.org/rtistatus.dat which are a cache\n"
"                            for Broadcom's data available at\n"
"                            https://gllto.glpals.com/7day/v5/latest/lto2.dat,\n"
"                            https://gllto.glpals.com/rto/v1/latest/rto.dat and\n"
"                            https://gllto.glpals.com/rtistatus4.dat. Alternatively, the standard\n"
"                            servers can be enabled in the Settings app which are\n"
"                            https://agnss.goog/lto2.dat, https://agnss.goog/rto.dat and\n"
"                            https://agnss.goog/rtistatus.dat providing a similar cache of\n"
"                            Broadcom's data currently (as of October 2022) hosted on GCP (Google\n"
"                            Cloud Platform)."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:941
msgid ""
"Pixel 4, Pixel 4 XL, Pixel 4a, Pixel 4a (5G), Pixel 5 and Pixel 5a\n"
"                            use a Qualcomm baseband providing cellular, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth and GNSS in\n"
"                            separate sandboxes), almanacs are downloaded from\n"
"                            https://qualcomm.psds.grapheneos.org/xtra3Mgrbeji.bin which is a cache\n"
"                            of Qualcomm's data. Alternatively, the standard servers can be enabled\n"
"                            in the Settings app which will use\n"
"                            https://path1.xtracloud.net/xtra3Mgrbeji.bin,\n"
"                            https://path2.xtracloud.net/xtra3Mgrbeji.bin and\n"
"                            https://path3.xtracloud.net/xtra3Mgrbeji.bin. GrapheneOS improves the\n"
"                            privacy of Qualcomm PSDS (XTRA) by removing the User-Agent header\n"
"                            normally containing an SoC serial number (unique hardware identifier),\n"
"                            random ID and information on the phone including manufacturer, brand\n"
"                            and model. We also always fetch the most complete XTRA database variant\n"
"                            (xtra3Mgrbeji.bin) instead of model/carrier/region dependent variants\n"
"                            to avoid leaking a small amount of information based on the database\n"
"                            variant."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:957
msgid ""
"Qualcomm Snapdragon SoC devices also fetch time via NTP for\n"
"                            xtra-daemon instead of using potentially incorrect OS time. We use\n"
"                            time.grapheneos.org when using the default GrapheneOS PSDS servers or\n"
"                            the standard time.xtracloud.net when using Qualcomm's servers. Stock\n"
"                            Pixel OS uses time.google.com but we follow Qualcomm's standard\n"
"                            settings to match other devices and to avoid the incompatible leap\n"
"                            second handling. These connections all go through the Owner VPN so it\n"
"                            isn't a real world fingerprinting issue."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:967
msgid ""
"Android devices launched with Android 8 or later provide support\n"
"                            for hardware-based attestation as part of the hardware keystore API.\n"
"                            Secure devices like Pixels provide both the traditional Trusted\n"
"                            Execution Environment (TrustZone) keystore and StrongBox keystore\n"
"                            based on a secure element, each providing attestation support. The\n"
"                            hardware-based attestation feature is a standard part of the Android\n"
"                            Open Source Project and are used to implement our Auditor app among\n"
"                            other things."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:975
msgid ""
"Initially, attestation signing keys were required to be batch keys\n"
"                            provisioned to at least 100k devices to avoid them being used as\n"
"                            unique identifiers. Unique attestation signing keys are an optional\n"
"                            feature only available to privileged system components. Recent devices\n"
"                            have replaced the batch and unique key system with remotely\n"
"                            provisioned signing keys. The device obtains encrypted keys from a\n"
"                            service to be decrypted by batch or unique keys inside the TEE and\n"
"                            optional secure element. The new system improves privacy and security\n"
"                            by using separate attestation signing keys for each app instead of\n"
"                            needing to balance privacy and security by sharing the same\n"
"                            attestation signing keys across a large batch of devices."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:986
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS uses https://remoteprovisioning.grapheneos.org/ by\n"
"                            default which is a private reverse proxy to the\n"
"                            https://remoteprovisioning.googleapis.com/ service. The service splits\n"
"                            up the implementation of provisioning to preserve privacy, and our\n"
"                            reverse proxy adds to that since it's unable to decrypt the\n"
"                            provisioned keys."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:992
msgid "A setting is added at "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:992
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                            Network &amp; internet &gt;\n"
"                            Attestation key provisioning"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:994
msgid ""
" for switching to directly using the\n"
"                            Google service if you prefer."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:996
msgid ""
"A future device built to run GrapheneOS as the stock OS would be\n"
"                            able to have a GrapheneOS attestation root and GrapheneOS attestation\n"
"                            key provisioning service rather than a GrapheneOS proxy. A device\n"
"                            built to run another OS without Google certification would need their\n"
"                            own service and we'd need to support proxying to that service too."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1003
msgid ""
"A test query is done via DNS-over-TLS in the automatic and manually\n"
"                            enabled modes to detect if DNS-over-TLS is available. It won't happen\n"
"                            when DNS-over-TLS is disabled. For the automatic mode, it uses this to\n"
"                            determine if it should be using it and for the manual mode it uses it\n"
"                            to report an error. This DNS query is not used to make a connection to\n"
"                            the resulting resolved IP."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1009
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS queries the DNS resolver for\n"
"                            "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1010
msgid ""
"\n"
"                            by default but switches to using the standard\n"
"                            "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1012
msgid ""
"\n"
"                            when the HTTP(S) connectivity check mode is set to Standard (Google)\n"
"                            instead of the default GrapheneOS mode or Disabled mode to avoid\n"
"                            identifying itself as GrapheneOS to the DNS resolver. The DNS-over-TLS\n"
"                            test query will still happen with HTTP(S) connectivity checks disabled\n"
"                            but DNS-over-TLS can be disabled by disabling Private DNS."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1018
msgid ""
"The random string is used to bypass DNS caching to make sure the\n"
"                            DNS resolver works. It's generated with a cryptographically secure\n"
"                            random number generator (CSPRNG) for each request and therefore can't\n"
"                            leak any identifying info."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1024
msgid ""
"DNS resolution for other connections involving connections to the\n"
"                            network/user provided DNS resolvers"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1028
msgid ""
"Other Vanadium browser connections are initiated by the user such as the\n"
"                    search engine (defaults to DuckDuckGo), websites and retrieving favicons for\n"
"                    your bookmarks and the frequent sites shown on the home page. We enable\n"
"                    connection and cache partitioning to keep connections separate between\n"
"                    different sites. There are a few parts of state partitioning still being\n"
"                    implemented including cookie partitioning which is currently in the testing\n"
"                    phase but causes too many compatibility issues to fully deploy it by default\n"
"                    without any exceptions like Brave's heuristics to disable it for cross-site\n"
"                    login flows, etc."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1037
msgid ""
"Unlike Chrome/Chromium, Vanadium WebView does not make connections beyond\n"
"                    those initiated by the app using it so there are no default connections from\n"
"                    apps using the WebView."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1042
msgid ""
"Which additional connections can the OS make\n"
"                    with a non-default configuration?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1044
msgid ""
"The previous section is an exhaustive list of all the default connections\n"
"                    made by a fresh GrapheneOS installation. Using a carrier, installing apps and\n"
"                    changing configuration can enable additional connections. This section aims to\n"
"                    list the cases which are not completely obvious to users. For example, if you\n"
"                    explicitly configure a Private DNS server, we don't need to explain here that\n"
"                    the OS will be connecting to that server."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1050
msgid ""
"Apps can list domains where they want to handle URLs instead of them being\n"
"                    handled by the browser. Domains officially associated with an app can add the\n"
"                    required metadata authorizing the app to automatically handle URLs which the\n"
"                    OS will fetch via HTTPS after installing the app to confirm if the app claims\n"
"                    to be authorized. See "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1054
msgid ""
"our usage guide\n"
"                    section on app link verification"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1055
msgid ""
" for more details such as how to block\n"
"                    these connections. The apps bundled with GrapheneOS don't require this and we\n"
"                    could hard-wire domains as verified if they did and we wanted to avoid more\n"
"                    default connections."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1059
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS uses\n"
"                    https://widevineprovisioning.grapheneos.org/certificateprovisioning/v1/devicecertificates/create\n"
"                    by default which is a private reverse proxy to\n"
"                    https://www.googleapis.com/certificateprovisioning/v1/devicecertificates/create\n"
"                    as part of Widevine provisioning. This is another form of key provisioning for\n"
"                    per-app keys that are used when playing DRM protected media. DRM support is\n"
"                    enabled in the OS by default but we don't include any apps using it by default,\n"
"                    since it's disabled in Vanadium. A setting is added at "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1066
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Network &amp; Internet &gt;\n"
"                    Widevine provisioning"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1067
msgid ""
" for switching to directly using the Google service if\n"
"                    you prefer."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1069
msgid ""
"Most other connections made by the OS itself are made based on your chosen\n"
"                    carrier. The OS has a database of APN and other carrier configuration settings\n"
"                    which determines how this works by default. Normally, carriers can force their\n"
"                    configuration choices on users by making APNs read-only and disabling various\n"
"                    configuration options. GrapheneOS ignores this and always allows configuring\n"
"                    APNs, APN types, changing preferred network mode, toggling off 2G and using\n"
"                    tethering regardless of what the carrier wants. We leave the defaults chosen\n"
"                    by the carriers alone. For example, if you want tethering traffic treated\n"
"                    normally, you can remove the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1077
msgid ""
" APN type from your APN\n"
"                    configuration."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1079
msgid ""
"When you have both a cellular connection and Location enabled, control\n"
"                    plane and/or user plane (SUPL) A-GNSS is used in addition to PSDS to greatly\n"
"                    reduce the time needed for GNSS to obtain an initial location lock. These\n"
"                    obtain coarse location info from a server based on nearby cell towers. Control\n"
"                    plane A-GNSS is provided by the cellular connection itself and therefore\n"
"                    doesn't have any real privacy implications while SUPL connects to a server\n"
"                    often not provided by the carrier. Most A-GNSS services only accelerate\n"
"                    obtaining a satellite-based location and won't provide an estimate on their\n"
"                    own. The carrier can choose a SUPL server as part of their carrier\n"
"                    configuration but most leave it at the default of supl.google.com. By default,\n"
"                    GrapheneOS overrides the carrier/fallback SUPL server and uses the\n"
"                    supl.grapheneos.org proxy. GrapheneOS adds a toggle for configuring SUPL in\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1091 static/releases.html:5688
msgid "Settings &gt; Location"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1091
msgid ""
" where you\n"
"                    can choose between the default "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1092
msgid "GrapheneOS proxy"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1092
msgid ""
" supl.grapheneos.org,\n"
"                    the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1093
msgid "Standard server"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1093
msgid " (carrier/fallback) or turning it "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1093
msgid ""
"\n"
"                    completely. GrapheneOS also disables sending IMSI and phone number as part of\n"
"                    SUPL. Pixels with a Qualcomm baseband use it to provide both cellular and GNSS\n"
"                    including both control plane and user plane A-GNSS being implemented inside\n"
"                    the baseband. For Qualcomm baseband devices, SUPL is only enabled if the APN\n"
"                    configuration for the carrier includes "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1098
msgid ""
" as an APN type.\n"
"                    Pixels with a Samsung baseband have a separate Broadcom or Samsung GNSS chip\n"
"                    without integration between them so SUPL is done by the OS with regular\n"
"                    networking (can use Wi-Fi and VPN) and SUPL is used regardless of the carrier's\n"
"                    APN type configuration."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1103
msgid ""
"MMS, RCS, SMS over LTE, VVM (Visual Voicemail), VoLTE (carrier-based calls\n"
"                    on 4G and higher), VoNR (5G) and VoWi-Fi are largely implemented by the OS via\n"
"                    TCP/IP rather than by the cellular layer itself. This means there will be\n"
"                    connections by the OS to carrier servers instead of being handled by cellular.\n"
"                    Most of these services (RCS, SMS over LTE, VVM, VoLTE, VoNR, and VoWi-Fi)\n"
"                    operate through the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) and involve connections to\n"
"                    the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1109
msgid ""
" domains. GrapheneOS modifies carrier\n"
"                    configuration so that toggles for disabling VoLTE, VoNR and VoWi-Fi are always\n"
"                    available. We plan to provide more toggles to control these things in the\n"
"                    future beyond making all the standard toggles available."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1116
msgid "GrapheneOS services follow the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1116
msgid ""
"EFF's\n"
"                    privacy-friendly Do Not Track (DNT) policy"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1117
msgid ""
" for all users of our publicly\n"
"                    available services, not just those opting out of tracking via Do Not Track. Our\n"
"                    policy is the same with \"DNT User\" redefined as \"user\" to cover any user. This\n"
"                    serves as a standard privacy policy across all of our public services:"
