#: static/faq.html:1144
msgid ""
"Our implementation of the policy primarily consists of making sure our\n"
"                    servers only retain logs for at most 10 days with a lower limit or no persistent\n"
"                    logs for certain services. In practice, we follow much stricter privacy\n"
"                    guidelines than the rules laid out in the EFF policy. However, we don't want to\n"
"                    define our own complex, ad-hoc privacy policy rather than reusing a sensible one\n"
"                    with serious thought put into it by experts."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1150
msgid ""
"Our mail server (mail.grapheneos.org), Matrix server (matrix.grapheneos.org),\n"
"                    Element instance (element.grapheneos.org) and Mastodon server\n"
"                    (grapheneos.social) only provide accounts for GrapheneOS project members so most\n"
"                    functionality is outside the scope of what's relevant to a public privacy\n"
"                    policy."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1158
msgid ""
"The OS uses the network-provided DNS servers by default. Typically, dynamic\n"
"                    IP configuration is used to auto-configure the client on the network. IPv4 DNS\n"
"                    servers are obtained via DHCP and IPv6 DNS servers are obtained via RDNSS. For\n"
"                    a static IP configuration, the DNS servers are manually configured as part of\n"
"                    the static configuration."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1163
msgid ""
"A VPN provides a network layered on top of the underlying networks and the\n"
"                    OS uses the VPN-provided DNS servers for everything beyond resolving the IP\n"
"                    address of the VPN and performing network connectivity checks on each of the\n"
"                    underlying networks in addition to the VPN itself."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1167
msgid ""
"Using the network-provided DNS servers is the best way to blend in with\n"
"                    other users. Network and web sites can fingerprint and track users based on a\n"
"                    non-default DNS configuration. Our recommendation for general purpose usage is\n"
"                    to use the network-provided DNS servers."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1171
msgid ""
"In some broken or unusual network environments, the network could fail to\n"
"                    provide DNS servers as part of dynamic IP configuration. The OS has high\n"
"                    availability fallback DNS servers to handle this case. A network can fail to\n"
"                    provide DNS servers in order to fingerprint clients based on what they use as\n"
"                    the fallback so it's important for it to be consistent across each install.\n"
"                    GrapheneOS replaces Google Public DNS with\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1177
msgid ""
"Cloudflare\n"
"                    DNS"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1178
msgid ""
" for the fallback DNS servers due to the superior privacy policy and\n"
"                    widespread usage including as the fallback DNS servers in other Android-based\n"
"                    operating systems. We're considering hosting our own servers and offering a\n"
"                    toggle for using the standard (Google) servers to blend in with other devices\n"
"                    similarly to how we handle the internet connectivity checks."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1186
msgid ""
"It isn't possible to directly override the DNS servers provided by the\n"
"                    network via DHCP. Instead, use the Private DNS feature in\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1188
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Network &amp;\n"
"                    internet &gt; Private DNS"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1189
msgid ""
" to set the\n"
"                    hostname of a DNS-over-TLS server. It needs to have a valid certificate such as a\n"
"                    free certificate from Let's Encrypt. The OS will look up the Private DNS hostname\n"
"                    via the network provided DNS servers and will then force all other DNS requests\n"
"                    through the Private DNS server. Unlike an option to override the network-provided\n"
"                    DNS servers, this prevents the network from monitoring or tampering with DNS\n"
"                    requests/responses."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1196
msgid "As an example, set the hostname to "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1196
msgid ""
" for Cloudflare DNS.\n"
"                    There are various other mainstream DNS-over-TLS options available including Quad9,\n"
"                    Google and AdGuard."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1199
msgid ""
"Configuring a static IP address for a network requires entering DNS servers\n"
"                    manually, but you should still use the Private DNS feature with it, and you shouldn't\n"
"                    misuse the static IP address option just to override the DNS servers."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1202
msgid ""
"VPN service apps can also provide their own DNS implementation and/or servers,\n"
"                    including an alternate implementation of encrypted DNS. Private DNS takes precedence\n"
"                    over VPN-provided DNS, since it's just the network-provided DNS."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1205
msgid ""
"Apps and web sites can detect the configured DNS servers by generating random\n"
"                    subdomains resolved by querying their authoritative DNS server. This can be used as\n"
"                    part of fingerprinting users. If you're using a VPN, you should consider using the\n"
"                    standard DNS service provided by the VPN service to avoid standing out from other\n"
"                    users."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1212
msgid "Why does Private DNS not accept IP addresses?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1213
msgid ""
"By default, in the automatic mode, the Private DNS feature provides opportunistic\n"
"                    encryption by using DNS-over-TLS when supported by the DNS server IP addresses\n"
"                    provided by the network (DHCP) or the static IP configuration. Opportunistic\n"
"                    encryption provides protection against a passive listener, not an active attacker,\n"
"                    since they can force falling back to unencrypted DNS by blocking DNS-over-TLS. In the\n"
"                    automatic mode, certificate validation is not enforced, as it would provide no\n"
"                    additional security and would reduce the availability of opportunistic encryption."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1220
msgid ""
"When Private DNS is explicitly enabled, it uses authenticated encryption without a\n"
"                    fallback. The authentication is performed based on the hostname of the server, so it\n"
"                    isn't possible to provide an IP address. The OS will look up the hostname of the Private\n"
"                    DNS server via unencrypted DNS and then force all other DNS lookups via DNS-over-TLS\n"
"                    with the identity of the server authenticated as part of providing authenticated\n"
"                    encryption."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1228
msgid "Does DNS-over-TLS (Private DNS) protect other connections?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1229
msgid ""
"No, it only provides privacy for DNS resolution. Even authenticating DNS results\n"
"                    with DNSSEC does not protect other connections, unless the DNS records are part of the\n"
"                    system used to provide authenticated encryption, and DNS-over-TLS is not a substitute\n"
"                    for DNSSEC. If connections have authenticated encryption, they're secure even if DNS\n"
"                    resolution is hijacked by an attacker. If connections do not have authenticated\n"
"                    encryption, an attacker can listen in and tamper with them without hijacking DNS.\n"
"                    There are other ways to perform a MITM attack than DNS hijacking and internet routing\n"
"                    is fundamentally insecure. DNS-over-TLS may make a MITM harder for some attackers, but\n"
"                    don't count on it at all."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1240
msgid "Does DNS-over-TLS (Private DNS) hide which sites are visited, etc.?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1241
msgid ""
"Private DNS only encrypts DNS, and an adversary monitoring connections can still\n"
"                    see the IP address at the other end of those connections. Many domains resolve to\n"
"                    ambiguous IP addresses, so encrypted DNS is part of what's required to take away a lot\n"
"                    of the information leaked to adversaries. However, TLS currently leaks domains via\n"
"                    SNI, so encrypted DNS is not yet accomplishing much. It's a forward looking feature\n"
"                    that will become more useful in the future. Using it is recommended, but it's not an\n"
"                    alternative to using Tor or a VPN."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1251
msgid "VPNs can be configured under "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1251
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    Network &amp; internet &gt; VPN"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1252
msgid ""
".\n"
"                    Support for the following protocols is included: IKEv2/IPSec MSCHAPv2,\n"
"                    IKEv2/IPSec PSK and IKEv2/IPSec RSA. Apps can also provide userspace VPN\n"
"                    implementations. The only apps we can recommend are the official WireGuard\n"
"                    app and the official Mullvad app. Mullvad's app is tested on GrapheneOS with\n"
"                    hardware memory tagging, unlike the official WireGuard app which has invalid\n"
"                    memory accesses detected by memory tagging if it's enabled. We recommend using\n"
"                    one of these VPN apps instead of the built-in IPSec VPN support."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1260
msgid ""
"VPN configurations created with the built-in support can be set as the\n"
"                    always-on VPN in the configuration panel. This will keep the VPN running,\n"
"                    reconnecting as necessary and will force all connections through them. An app\n"
"                    providing a VPN service can also be set as the always-on VPN via the entry in\n"
"                    the Settings page. For app-based VPN implementations, there's also an\n"
"                    additional \"Block connections without VPN\" toggle which is needed to prevent\n"
"                    leaks when the app's VPN service isn't running."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1267
msgid ""
"If you're using a VPN, we recommended against having a Private DNS server\n"
"                    configured. If you want to filter traffic while using a VPN, use a VPN service\n"
"                    app able to do both such as RethinkDNS. Private DNS also interacts strangely\n"
"                    with multiple profiles since each profile has their own VPN configuration but\n"
"                    Private DNS is global. "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1271
msgid ""
"We strongly recommend fully disabling Private DNS\n"
"                    when using a VPN on any secondary profile until it's overhauled."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1275
msgid "Can apps monitor network connections or statistics?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1276
msgid ""
"Apps cannot monitor network connections unless they're made into the active\n"
"                    VPN service by the user. Apps cannot normally access network stats and cannot\n"
"                    directly request access to them. However, app-based stats can be explicitly\n"
"                    granted by users as part of access to app usage stats in\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1280
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Apps &gt; Special app access &gt;\n"
"                    Usage access"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1282
msgid ""
"This was previously part of the GrapheneOS privacy improvements, but became a\n"
"                    standard Android feature with Android 10."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1287
msgid ""
"Yes, GrapheneOS inherits the deeply integrated firewall from the Android\n"
"                    Open Source Project, which is used to implement portions of the security model\n"
"                    and various other features. The GrapheneOS project historically made various\n"
"                    improvements to the firewall but over time most of these changes have been\n"
"                    integrated upstream or became irrelevant."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1292
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds a user-facing Network permission toggle providing a robust\n"
"                    way to deny both direct and indirect network access to applications. It builds\n"
"                    upon the standard non-user-facing INTERNET permission, so it's already fully\n"
"                    adopted by the app ecosystem. Revoking the permission denies indirect access\n"
"                    via OS components and apps enforcing the INTERNET permission, such as\n"
"                    DownloadManager. Direct access is denied by blocking low-level network socket\n"
"                    access. A packet-based firewall would only block direct access so our approach\n"
"                    is much more complete. Additionally, GrapheneOS pretends that the Network is\n"
"                    down for most APIs when the Network permission is disabled. For example, it\n"
"                    won't run scheduled jobs depending internet availability and most APIs for\n"
"                    checking the state of the network will report it as down and internet access\n"
"                    as unavailable. This means apps won't try to keep trying to access the\n"
"                    internet and draining battery because they'll treat it the way they do when\n"
"                    internet access is genuinely unavailable."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1309
msgid ""
"The recommended approach to system-wide ad-blocking is setting up\n"
"                    domain-based ad-blocking as part of DNS resolution. You can do this by\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1311
msgid "choosing a Private DNS (DNS-over-TLS) server"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1311
msgid ""
" with\n"
"                    support for blocking ad domains. As an example, AdGuard DNS can be used by\n"
"                    setting "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1313
msgid ""
" as the Private DNS domain. This feature\n"
"                    used to be included by the project many years ago, but it needs to be\n"
"                    reimplemented, and it's a low priority feature depending on contributors\n"
"                    stepping up to work on it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1317
msgid ""
"Apps and web sites can detect that ad-blocking is being used and can\n"
"                    determine what's being blocked. This can be used as part of fingerprinting\n"
"                    users. Using a widely used service like AdGuard with a standard block list is\n"
"                    much less of an issue than a custom set of subscriptions and rules, but it still\n"
"                    stands out compared to the default of not doing it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1325
msgid ""
"Content filtering apps are fully compatible with GrapheneOS, but they have\n"
"                    serious drawbacks and using apps doing more than DNS-based filtering are not\n"
"                    recommended. These apps use the VPN service feature to route traffic through\n"
"                    themselves to perform filtering."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1329
msgid ""
"The approach of intercepting traffic is inherently incompatible with encryption\n"
"                    from the client to the server. The AdGuard app works around encryption by supporting\n"
"                    optional\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1332
msgid "HTTPS interception"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1332
msgid ""
" by\n"
"                    having the user trust a local certificate authority, which is a security risk and\n"
"                    weakens HTTPS security even if their implementation is flawless (which they openly\n"
"                    acknowledge in their documentation, although it understates the risks). It also can't\n"
"                    intercept connections using certificate pinning, with the exception of browsers which\n"
"                    go out of the way to allow overriding pinning with locally added certificate\n"
"                    authorities. Many of these apps only provide domain-based filtering, unlike the deeper\n"
"                    filtering by AdGuard, but they're still impacted by encryption due to Private DNS\n"
"                    (DNS-over-TLS) and require disabling the feature. They could provide their own\n"
"                    DNS-over-TLS resolver to avoid losing the feature, but few of the developers care\n"
"                    enough to do that."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1343
msgid ""
"Using the VPN service to provide something other than a VPN also means that these\n"
"                    apps need to provide an actual VPN implementation or a way to forward to apps\n"
"                    providing one, and very few have bothered to implement this."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1346
msgid ""
"RethinkDNS combines local filtering via DNS with the ability to directly\n"
"                    use a WireGuard VPN without another app. It also has other features such as\n"
"                    connection monitoring. This is a much better approach than most of the apps in\n"
"                    this space which force choosing between them and a VPN, recommend problematic\n"
"                    TLS interception (AdGuard), etc."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1354
msgid ""
"Yes, the baseband is isolated on all of the officially supported devices. Memory\n"
"                    access is partitioned by the IOMMU and limited to internal memory and memory shared\n"
"                    by the driver implementations. The baseband on the officially supported devices with a\n"
"                    Qualcomm SoC implements Wi-Fi and Bluetooth as internal sandboxed processes rather\n"
"                    than having a separate baseband for those like earlier devices."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1359
msgid ""
"Earlier generation devices we used to support prior to Pixels had Wi-Fi + Bluetooth\n"
"                    implemented on a separate SoC. This was not properly contained by the stock OS and we\n"
"                    put substantial work into addressing that problem. However, that work has been\n"
"                    obsoleted now that Wi-Fi and Bluetooth are provided by the SoC on the officially\n"
"                    supported devices."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1364
msgid ""
"A component being on a separate chip is orthogonal to whether it's isolated. In\n"
"                    order to be isolated, the drivers need to treat it as untrusted. If it has DMA access,\n"
"                    that needs to be contained via IOMMU and the driver needs to treat the shared memory\n"
"                    as untrusted, as it would do with data received another way. There's a lot of attack\n"
"                    surface between the baseband and the kernel/userspace software stack connected to it.\n"
"                    OS security is very relevant to containing hardware components including the radios and\n"
"                    the vast majority of the attack surface is in software. The OS relies upon the\n"
"                    hardware and firmware to be able to contain components but ends up being primarily\n"
"                    responsible for it due to control over the configuration of shared memory and the\n"
"                    complexity of the interface and the OS side implementation."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1374
msgid ""
"The mobile Atheros Wi-Fi driver/firmware is primarily a SoftMAC implementation with\n"
"                    the vast majority of the complexity in the driver rather than the firmware. The fully\n"
"                    functional driver is massive and the firmware is quite small. Unfortunately, since the\n"
"                    Linux kernel is monolithic and has no internal security boundaries, the attack surface\n"
"                    is problematic and a HardMAC implementation with most complexity in the isolated\n"
"                    firmware could be better than the status quo. An isolated driver would be ideal."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1383
msgid ""
"If you are seeing this warning when setting up your device after GrapheneOS\n"
"                    has been installed, it means that not all of the installation steps have been\n"
"                    completed. This can be remediated by finishing the installation process and\n"
"                    locking the device's bootloader."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1387
msgid "To do this, follow these steps:"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1389
msgid "Navigate to the bootloader locking section of the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1389
msgid ""
"web install\n"
"                            (recommended)"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:92
#: static/faq.html:1390
msgid " or "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1390
msgid "CLI install"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1390
msgid ""
"\n"
"                            guide on the device you'll be using to lock the bootloader."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1392
msgid "If you are at the welcome screen on your GrapheneOS device, tap \"Next\"."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1393
msgid "On the resulting screen, tap \"Reboot to bootloader\"."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1394
msgid ""
"Connect your GrapheneOS device to the device where you have the install page"
" open."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1395
msgid "Follow the steps on the install page to lock the bootloader."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1396
msgid ""
"Once locked, you can start setting up your GrapheneOS device, and the "
"warning should no longer be present."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1398
msgid ""
"It is important to note that this is something that should be done before\n"
"                    placing any data onto the device, as until this step is completed, the device is\n"
"                    considered to be insecure. Please note that locking the bootloader wipes all\n"
"                    user data on the device. GrapheneOS doesn't provide any support to users running\n"
"                    GrapheneOS with an unlocked bootloader, as this is considered to be an\n"
"                    incomplete installation."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1410
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS has entirely automatic background updates. More details are\n"
"                    available in the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1411
msgid ""
"the usage guide's updates\n"
"                    section"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1415
msgid "How do I update without connecting the device to the internet?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1416
msgid "Updates can be "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1416
msgid ""
"sideloaded via\n"
"                    recovery"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1420
msgid "Do notifications work properly on GrapheneOS?"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1421
msgid ""
"Yes, notifications work properly on GrapheneOS. Portable apps avoiding a\n"
"                    hard dependency on Google Play services for their functionality have fully\n"
"                    working notifications on GrapheneOS. Apps that are not fully portable across\n"
"                    Android implementations often lack support for background notifications due to\n"
"                    only bothering to implement support for it via Google Play services."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1426
msgid ""
"Most apps that are able to run without Google Play services will have\n"
"                    working notifications when they're in the foreground. Unfortunately, many apps\n"
"                    don't implement a service to continue receiving events from their server in\n"
"                    the background. On the stock OS, they rely on receiving events through Google\n"
"                    servers via Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM) in the background and sometimes\n"
"                    even in the foreground, although it doesn't have good reliability/latency."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1432
msgid ""
"Polling is the traditional pull-based approach of checking for new events\n"
"                    at an interval. This is badly suited to mobile devices for anything more than\n"
"                    very infrequent checks. Apps using infrequent polling are supposed to use the\n"
"                    JobScheduler service. A minority of apps may only know how to use Firebase\n"
"                    WorkManager or the legacy Firebase JobDispatcher. Most apps know how to use\n"
"                    JobScheduler rather than depending on Google Play services for the Firebase\n"
"                    services. Typical examples of apps using this approach are a feed reader for\n"
"                    RSS/Atom feeds or an email client providing notifications of new emails for a\n"
"                    server without IMAP IDLE push support."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1441
msgid ""
"Push messaging is the modern push-based model of receiving events from the\n"
"                    server as they occur by keeping open a connection to it. Push messaging still\n"
"                    uses occasional polling to keep the connection from being killed by a network\n"
"                    using a stateful firewall or some form of NAT. IPv4 mobile networks use large\n"
"                    scale NAT (CGNAT) to work around IPv4 addresses running out. The occasional\n"
"                    polling will also detect a silently dropped connection. An efficient push\n"
"                    implementation will figure out that it's on a reliable network and throttle\n"
"                    the polling to be very infrequent."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1449
msgid ""
"In order to properly implement either push messaging or frequent polling\n"
"                    themselves, an app needs to run a foreground service. This is displayed as a\n"
"                    persistent notification. It will normally be marked as a silent notification\n"
"                    with the lowest possible default importance for a foreground service\n"
"                    (IMPORTANCE_LOW). It can be reduced to the lowest importance (IMPORTANCE_MIN)\n"
"                    by the user if they set the notification channel to be collapsed which will\n"
"                    collapse it in the notification tray and it won't show up as an icon in the\n"
"                    status bar or on the lockscreen anymore. Users can also disable the\n"
"                    notification and the foreground service will continue working. A battery\n"
"                    optimization exception is also needed for the app to bypass device idle states\n"
"                    and run while the device is idle. If you can tolerate delays while the device\n"
"                    is idle, then the battery optimization exception isn't mandatory."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1461
msgid ""
"FairEmail and Signal are examples of apps using the proper approach of a\n"
"                    foreground service combined with an optional battery optimization exception.\n"
"                    Signal doesn't have an optimized implementation throttling the polling used to\n"
"                    keep the connection alive, but it does work well. Signal always uses their own\n"
"                    push implementation in the foreground, but switches to FCM in the background\n"
"                    when it's available. FairEmail uses the IMAP IDLE push feature provided by\n"
"                    email servers. Most email servers don't provide FCM-based push in the first\n"
"                    place, and the only way for an email app to provide push via FCM would be to\n"
"                    give the user's credentials to their own server to act as a middleman."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1473
msgid ""
"Files can be transferred to another device using an external drive, USB file\n"
"                    transfer via MTP and PTP, or an app-based mechanism."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1475
msgid ""
"The only difference on GrapheneOS is that by default the USB-C port and pogo\n"
"                    pins block new connections as soon as the device is locked by default and\n"
"                    disable USB data when any existing connections end. The default behavior won't\n"
"                    interfere with this use case at all. If you've changed it to a stricter value\n"
"                    such as completely disallowing USB-C data, it can be changed back to the default\n"
"                    \"Charging-only when locked\" value in\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1481
msgid "Settings &gt; Security &gt; Exploit protection &gt; USB-C port"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1482
msgid ""
"To use an external drive, plug it into the phone and use the system file\n"
"                    manager to copy files to and from it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1484
msgid ""
"Transferring files to an attached computer is done with MTP and PTP. Users on\n"
"                    a Mac computer will need to install "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1485
msgid "OpenMTP"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1485
msgid ""
" or another MTP app to be able\n"
"                    to transfer files between macOS and Android. After plugging in the phone to the\n"
"                    computer, there will be a notification showing the current USB mode with\n"
"                    charging as the default. Pressing the notification acts as a shortcut to\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1489
msgid "Settings &gt; Connected devices &gt; USB"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1489
msgid ". You can enable "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1489
msgid "File Transfer"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1489
msgid ""
" (MTP)\n"
"                    or "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1490
msgid "PTP"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1490
msgid ""
" with this menu. It will provide read/write access to the entire\n"
"                    profile home directory, i.e. the top-level directory named after the device in\n"
"                    the system file manager which does not include internal app data. Due to needing\n"
"                    to trust the computer with coarse-grained access, we recommend transferring\n"
"                    files with a flash drive or by sending the files to yourself via an end-to-end\n"
"                    encrypted messaging app like Element (Matrix)."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1500
msgid ""
"Like the Android Open Source Project, GrapheneOS doesn't include Google apps\n"
"                and services. They won't ever be bundled with the OS. GrapheneOS includes a\n"
"                compatibility layer for sandboxed Play services to make user installed Play\n"
"                services apps able to run as fully sandboxed, unprivileged apps. This is "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1503
msgid "documented as part of the usage guide"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1503
msgid ""
".\n"
"                Many apps work perfectly without Play services and many others only depend on it\n"
"                for a subset of their functionality. Users can choose to install Play services in\n"
"                specific profile(s) to control which apps can use it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1507
msgid ""
"AOSP APIs not tied to Google but that are typically provided via Play services\n"
"                will continue to be implemented using open source providers like the Seedvault\n"
"                backup app. Text-to-speech, speech-to-text, geocoding, accessibility services,\n"
"                etc. are examples of other open Android APIs where we need to develop/bundle an\n"
"                implementation based on existing open source projects. GrapheneOS is not going to\n"
"                be implementing these via a Google service compatibility layer because these APIs\n"
"                are in no way inherently tied to Google services."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1514
msgid ""
"Ideally, Google themselves would support installing the official Play services\n"
"                as regular apps rather than taking the monopolistic approach of forcing it to be\n"
"                bundled into the OS in a deeply integrated way with special privileged permissions\n"
"                and capabilities unavailable to other service providers competing with them. Until\n"
"                that happens, if ever, GrapheneOS can continue teaching it to function that way to\n"
"                the extent possible without any special privileges."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1523 static/index.html:60 static/usage.html:41
msgid "features page"
msgstr "página de funciones"

#: static/faq.html:1527
msgid ""
"No, since this is strictly a theft deterrence feature, not a security feature,\n"
"                and the standard implementation depends on having the device tied to an account on\n"
"                an online service. The only advantage would be encouraging thieves to return a\n"
"                stolen device for a potential reward after realizing that it has no value beyond\n"
"                scrapping it for parts."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1532
msgid ""
"Google's Factory Reset Protection ties devices to a Google account using a\n"
"                tiny, special region of persistent state not wiped by a factory reset. It prevents\n"
"                a thief from wiping the device to a fresh state for resale without being stuck at\n"
"                a screen for authenticating with the Google account persisted on the device after\n"
"                wiping. Google's approach works well because if users forget their Google\n"
"                password, there are account recovery methods available to avoid a bricked\n"
"                phone."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1539
msgid ""
"It would be possible to make an implementation not reliant upon an online\n"
"                service where the user has the option to enable Factory Reset Protection and is\n"
"                given a seed phrase required to use the device after wiping data from recovery.\n"
"                However, since this has no security value and the ability to deter theft is\n"
"                questionable, implementing this is an extremely low priority. Users will end up\n"
"                with a bricked phone if they lose the seed phrase and need to wipe the phone after\n"
"                forgetting their passphrase or something else causing them to need to wipe such as\n"
"                breaking the OS via the Android Debug Bridge shell. Bricked phones would be a far\n"
"                bigger problem than any theft deterrence this could provide. This approach may be\n"
"                implemented by GrapheneOS in some form in the future but it's a low priority and\n"
"                we don't want to cause people to brick their phones. We won't be able to offer any\n"
"                help if people brick their phones with this."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1551
msgid ""
"Providing the option to disable wiping from recovery would be simpler, but\n"
"                would be incompatible with features designed to wipe data automatically in certain\n"
"                cases. It would also result in far more bricked phones than the seed phrase\n"
"                approach describe above since setting a new lock method and forgetting it which is\n"
"                a relatively common occurrence would mean a bricked phone. This will not be\n"
"                implemented by GrapheneOS since it isn't a good approach and it conflicts with\n"
"                other planned features."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1561
msgid ""
"There are drawbacks to bundling apps into the OS and few advantages in most\n"
"                cases. Rather than GrapheneOS bundling a bunch of apps, it makes far more sense for\n"
"                users to install their preferred apps from the developers and various app stores.\n"
"                GrapheneOS also has a first party app update system for a first party repository\n"
"                with higher robustness and security than the existing options. Rather than bundling\n"
"                apps, it could just offer recommendations as part of an initial setup wizard. Users\n"
"                have unique needs and preferences and there has to be a very compelling reason to\n"
"                bundle additional apps with the OS. For example, it's useful to have the Auditor app\n"
"                available before connecting to the internet (see the\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1570
msgid ""
"installation guide documentation on\n"
"                this"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1571
msgid ")."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1572
msgid ""
"Bundling additional apps with the OS can increase attack surface, unless users go\n"
"                out of the way to disable apps they aren't using. Bundling an app into the base OS is\n"
"                also painful to reverse, since removing the app without implementing a migration\n"
"                mechanism will lose user data stored in the app. Some users are also going to take\n"
"                issue with the choices made by the project or will want to make suggestions for\n"
"                bundling more apps, and having this as a regular topic of discussion and debate is\n"
"                unproductive and distracts from the real work of the project. Each bundled app also\n"
"                increases the size of the base OS, and shipping the app updates as part of the OS\n"
"                updates results in more overall bandwidth usage. It would be possible to ship only\n"
"                out-of-band app updates to avoid wasted bandwidth for apps users have disabled, but\n"
"                then the apps would be temporarily out-of-date and vulnerable to patched security\n"
"                issues after a factory reset or the user re-enabling them. If the updates aren't going\n"
"                to be shipped with the OS, it really makes no sense to bundle them."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1585
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS is focused on making meaningful improvements to privacy and security,\n"
"                and bundling assorted apps into the OS is not only usually outside of that focus but\n"
"                often counter to it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1588
msgid ""
"In some cases, licensing is also an issue. GrapheneOS is permissively licensed and\n"
"                is usable for building devices with an immutable root of trust. GPLv3 is deliberately\n"
"                incompatible with these kinds of locked down devices, unlike GPLv2 code such as the\n"
"                Linux kernel. This means GrapheneOS can't include GPLv3 code without forbidding use\n"
"                cases we want to support. GPLv3 is no problem for our own usage, but we don't want to\n"
"                forbid using GrapheneOS as a replacement for the Android Open Source Project in locked\n"
"                down devices."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1598
msgid ""
"To get an idea of the near term roadmap, check out the\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1599
msgid ""
". The vast majority of the\n"
"                issues filed in the trackers are planned enhancements, with care taken to make sure\n"
"                all of the issues open in the tracker are concrete and actionable."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1602
msgid ""
"In the long term, GrapheneOS aims to move beyond a hardened fork of the Android\n"
"                Open Source Project. Achieving the goals requires moving away from relying on the Linux\n"
"                kernel as the core of the OS and foundation of the security model. It needs to move\n"
"                towards a microkernel-based model with a Linux compatibility layer, with many stepping\n"
"                stones leading towards that goal including adopting virtualization-based\n"
"                isolation."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1608
msgid ""
"The initial phase for the long-term roadmap of moving away from the current\n"
"                foundation will be to deploy and integrate\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1610
msgid "pKVM"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1610
msgid ""
"\n"
"                and CrosVM, reinforcing existing security boundaries. The Android Open Source\n"
"                Project has been making significant progress on this front, so our next milestone is\n"
"                to securely deploy Android apps using this virtualization setup. In the longer term,\n"
"                Linux inside the sandboxes can be replaced with a compatibility layer like gVisor,\n"
"                which would need to be given a new backend alongside the existing KVM backend. Over\n"
"                the longer term, i.e. many years from now, Linux and the usage of virtualization can\n"
"                fade away completely. The anticipation is that many other projects are going to be\n"
"                interested in this kind of migration, so it's not going to be solely a GrapheneOS\n"
"                project; this is demonstrated by the current existence and development of gVisor and\n"
"                pKVM, as well as various other projects working on virtualization deployments for\n"
"                mobile. Having a hypervisor with verified boot still intact will also provide a way\n"
"                to achieve some of the goals based on extensions to Trusted Execution Environment\n"
"                (TEE) functionality even without having GrapheneOS hardware."
msgstr ""

