#: static/faq.html:1693
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS has made substantial contributions to the privacy and security of\n"
"                the Android Open Source Project, along with contributions to the Linux kernel,\n"
"                LLVM, OpenBSD and other projects. Much of our past work is no longer part of the\n"
"                downstream GrapheneOS project because we've successfully landed many patches\n"
"                upstream. We've had even more success with making suggestions and participating in\n"
"                design discussions to steer things in the direction we want. Many upstream changes\n"
"                in AOSP such as removing app access to low-level process, network, timing and\n"
"                profiling information originated in the GrapheneOS project. The needs of the\n"
"                upstream projects are often different from ours, so they'll often reimplement the\n"
"                features in a more flexible way. We've almost always been able to move to using\n"
"                the upstream features and even when we still need our own implementation it helps\n"
"                to have the concepts/restrictions considered by the upstream project and apps\n"
"                needing to be compatible with it. Getting features upstream often leads to an\n"
"                improved user experience and app compatibility."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1710
msgid ""
"Yes, the GrapheneOS code is reviewed by external security researchers,\n"
"                companies and organizations on a continuous basis. This is the main benefit of\n"
"                GrapheneOS being an open source project actively used by other organizations, but\n"
"                it is certainly not something to take for granted based on a project being open\n"
"                source. We put a lot of work into making our code well documented and easy to\n"
"                review. Auditing and code review cannot be done properly as a one time thing but\n"
"                rather need to be done continuously as the code changes. Most of the code review\n"
"                and auditing results for GrapheneOS can be seen from the public pull requests and\n"
"                issue trackers. For example, the French\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1719
msgid "ANSSI organization"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1719
msgid ""
" uses a bunch of our\n"
"                work and has given us suggestions along with reporting issues including a couple\n"
"                issues in hardened_malloc where it could have a false positive detection of memory\n"
"                corruption and wrongly abort the process."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1722
msgid "[1]"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1722
msgid "[2]"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1722
msgid ""
"\n"
"                We've built relationships with security researchers and organizations interested\n"
"                in GrapheneOS or using it which results in a lot of this kind of collaboration.\n"
"                This is not a one-time event but rather something that happens regularly as the\n"
"                code evolves, features are added and we ported to new release. The benefits of a\n"
"                group unfamiliar with the code spending a short time doing a shallow review are\n"
"                greatly overstated in marketing. We instead focus on having people very familiar\n"
"                with areas of the code regularly auditing all our changes. The large number of\n"
"                upstream Android security vulnerabilities discovered by GrapheneOS despite us not\n"
"                actively seeking them out speaks to the results of our review and testing."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1732
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS code is not just open source but well documented and organized in\n"
"                order to make it much easier to review. Every change we make to Android Open\n"
"                Source Project repositories is maintained as a clean patch set on top of the\n"
"                latest stable release of AOSP. We regularly clean up our changes by splitting up\n"
"                the commits in a more sensible way, providing better commit messages, stripping\n"
"                away everything but the essential changes, reordering the commits to group the\n"
"                related changes and improving the implementation. This makes sense because these\n"
"                are downstream changes ported between each stable release. Our approach also makes\n"
"                it easy to port our patches elsewhere including upstreaming them. Ease of porting\n"
"                helps us when we port to new quarterly and yearly major releases of AOSP. The best\n"
"                way to review our changes over time is the "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1742
msgid ""
" command by\n"
"                passing the old range of commits and the new range of commits. For example, you\n"
"                would pass "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1745
msgid ""
" to see how our changes on top of AOSP have\n"
"                changed between releases without looking at the upstream AOSP changes. This is a\n"
"                major part of our own regular review of our changes and porting work."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1748
msgid ""
"Our own standalone projects such as Auditor and AttestationServer also aim to\n"
"                keep the code very easy to audit/review. In those projects, we're writing all the\n"
"                code and choosing the dependencies ourselves, so we can take a minimalist and easy\n"
"                to understand approach to the overall codebase instead of only our changes to\n"
"                it."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1753
msgid ""
"We also get broad code review out of attempting to land changes in upstream\n"
"                projects. For example, our CONFIG_FORTIFY_SOURCE feature for the Linux kernel\n"
"                providing a modern take on that feature with support for detecting both read and\n"
"                write overflows was accepted in the Linux kernel in 2017. It has taken several\n"
"                years for all the extra bits of CONFIG_FORTIFY_SOURCE to be accepted upstream.\n"
"                Substantial improvements have been made as part of upstreaming it including\n"
"                upstream deciding to support detecting overflows within objects for the memory\n"
"                family of functions, going far beyond the traditional approach. Based on our\n"
"                issue reports and recommendations, multiple bugs were fixed in both GCC and Clang\n"
"                for FORTIFY_SOURCE support along with a new feature for more dynamic object size\n"
"                checks being added. Android also ended up shipping automatic array bounds checks\n"
"                in addition to FORTIFY_SOURCE for the kernel. We would not have been able to do\n"
"                the same level of testing to uncover the same number of upstream bugs, and we also\n"
"                couldn't have made the more aggressive changes on our own due to lack of resources\n"
"                to review/test the upstream code for compatibility issues."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1771
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS was founded as an open source project in 2014. It has been through\n"
"                multiple renames and wasn't initially known as GrapheneOS. See the\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1773
msgid "history page"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1773 static/faq.html:1780 static/features.html:624
msgid " for more details."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1777
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS was previously known as CopperheadOS. There's a new closed source\n"
"                product using our legacy CopperheadOS branding and code that's not associated with\n"
"                the original project. See "
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1779
msgid ""
"our page on the legacy\n"
"                CopperheadOS branding"
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1784
msgid ""
"No, GrapheneOS will remain a non-profit open source project and organization. It\n"
"                will remain an independent organization not strongly associated with any specific\n"
"                company. We partner with a variety of companies and other organizations, and we're\n"
"                interested in more partnerships in the future. Keeping it as an non-profit avoids\n"
"                the conflicts of interest created by a profit-based model. It allows us to focus\n"
"                on improving privacy/security without struggling to build a viable business model\n"
"                that's not in conflict with the success of the open source project."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1794
msgid ""
"The copyright for GrapheneOS code is entirely owned by the GrapheneOS developers\n"
"                and is made available under OSI-approved Open Source licenses. The upstream licensing\n"
"                is inherited for the modifications to those projects and MIT licensing is used for our\n"
"                own standalone projects. GrapheneOS has never had any copyright assignment and the\n"
"                developers have always owned their own contributions, including for code written\n"
"                from 2014 up to the rebranding to GrapheneOS in 2019."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1800
msgid ""
"There was an era from September 2016 until the project split from the former\n"
"                sponsor in 2018 where non-commercial usage licensing was used for the official\n"
"                builds and from January 2017 onwards for revisions to the existing permissively\n"
"                licensed code. This was an attempt to prop up the sponsor that was supposed to be\n"
"                supporting the open source project. This did not impact ownership of the code and\n"
"                the copyright owners have relicensed the portions of the code that are used by\n"
"                GrapheneOS under open source licenses. GrapheneOS does not contain any code based\n"
"                on code under non-commercial usage licensing."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1811
msgid ""
"The GrapheneOS name and logo are trademarks of the GrapheneOS project. Both\n"
"                are registered in the United States with serial numbers 90746220 and 90746226. The\n"
"                marks are also in the process of being formally registered in Canada. In the\n"
"                meantime, they're protected as common law trademarks."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1815
msgid ""
"Derivatives of GrapheneOS that are being published/redistributed should replace\n"
"                the GrapheneOS branding with their own. It needs to be clear to users that it's a\n"
"                distinct OS based on GrapheneOS. Forks of GrapheneOS are not GrapheneOS itself and\n"
"                should not be presented that way."
msgstr ""

#: static/faq.html:1819
msgid ""
"Only unofficial builds of the official GrapheneOS sources should be referred to\n"
"                as unofficial builds. An unofficial build is a build of the official GrapheneOS\n"
"                sources with the update server URL changed to another server. A project making\n"
"                modifications beyond that isn't simply an unofficial build and should be presented\n"
"                as a distinct OS based on GrapheneOS."
msgstr ""

