#: static/features.html:257
msgid ""
", which significantly\n"
"                        reduces attack surface when the device is locked. After locking, it blocks\n"
"                        any new USB connections immediately through either USB-C and pogo pins at\n"
"                        both the hardware level via configuring the USB controller and also at the\n"
"                        OS level in the kernel to provide a second layer of defense. It disables the\n"
"                        data lines at a hardware level as soon as the existing connections end which\n"
"                        happens right away if there were no USB connections. It also disables USB-C\n"
"                        alternate modes including DisplayPort at both the OS and hardware level."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:265
msgid ""
"Our implementation is far more secure than Android's standard USB HAL\n"
"                        toggle available to device admin apps. The standard feature only disables\n"
"                        high level USB handling in the OS. It doesn't block new USB connections or\n"
"                        disable the data lines at a hardware level. It also leaves the handling of\n"
"                        the USB-C and pogo pins protocols enabled in the OS, and it doesn't disable\n"
"                        the USB-C alternate modes. The standard feature is also either blocking or\n"
"                        not blocking USB at a high level, without the ability to block new\n"
"                        connections and disable USB only once the existing connections end. Other\n"
"                        operating systems trying to implement a similar feature via the standard\n"
"                        toggle end up continuing to allow new USB connections in the OS until all\n"
"                        connections end instead of the two-phase approach we use for our two\n"
"                        Charging-only when locked modes."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:277
msgid "The highest security "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:277
msgid ""
" mode disables charging in addition to\n"
"                        data to remove the remaining attack surface from the USB controller and OS\n"
"                        supporting charging including the USB-PD protocol. There's no risk of the\n"
"                        device not being able to be charged since the overall feature doesn't apply\n"
"                        while the device is powered off, booted into the firmware-based fastboot\n"
"                        mode or the charging, recovery and fastbootd modes."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:285
msgid "Exploit mitigations"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:287
msgid "Hardened app runtime"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:288
msgid ""
"Secure application spawning\n"
"                            system"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:289
msgid ""
" avoiding sharing address space layout and other secrets\n"
"                            across applications"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:291
msgid "Hardened libc"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:291
msgid ""
"\n"
"                            providing defenses against the most common classes of vulnerabilities (memory\n"
"                            corruption)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:294
msgid ""
"\n"
"                                Our own "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:295
msgid ""
"hardened\n"
"                                malloc (memory allocator)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:296
msgid ""
" leveraging modern hardware capabilities\n"
"                                to provide substantial defenses against the most common classes of\n"
"                                vulnerabilities (heap memory corruption) along with reducing the lifetime\n"
"                                of sensitive data in memory. The "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:299
msgid ""
"hardened_malloc\n"
"                                README"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:300
msgid ""
" has extensive documentation on it. The hardened_malloc\n"
"                                project is portable to other Linux-based operating systems and is being\n"
"                                adopted by other security-focused operating systems like secureblue. Our\n"
"                                allocator also heavily influenced the design of the "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:303
msgid ""
"next-generation\n"
"                                musl malloc implementation"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:304
msgid ""
" which offers substantially better security than\n"
"                                musl's previous malloc while still having minimal memory usage and code size.\n"
"                                "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:307
msgid ""
"Fully out-of-line metadata with protection from corruption, ruling\n"
"                                    out traditional allocator exploitation"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:309
msgid ""
"Separate memory regions for metadata, large allocations and each\n"
"                                    slab allocation size class with high entropy random bases and no\n"
"                                    address space reuse between the different regions"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:312
msgid "Deterministic detection of any invalid free"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:313
msgid ""
"Zero-on-free with detection of write-after-free via checking that\n"
"                                    memory is still zeroed before handing it out again"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:315
msgid ""
"Delayed reuse of address space and memory allocations through the\n"
"                                    combination of deterministic and randomized quarantines to mitigate\n"
"                                    use-after-free vulnerabilities"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:318
msgid "Fine-grained randomization"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:319
msgid "Aggressive consistency checks"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:320
msgid ""
"Memory protected guard regions around allocations larger than 16k\n"
"                                    with randomization of guard region sizes for 128k and above"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:322
msgid ""
"Allocations smaller than 16k have guard regions around each of the\n"
"                                    slabs containing allocations (for example, 16 byte allocations are in\n"
"                                    4096 byte slabs with 4096 byte guard regions before and after)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:325
msgid ""
"Random canaries with a leading zero are added to these smaller\n"
"                                    allocations to block C string overflows, absorb small overflows\n"
"                                    and detect linear overflows or other heap corruption when the\n"
"                                    canary value is checked (primarily on free)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:329
msgid ""
"Hardware memory tagging for slab allocations (128k and\n"
"                                    below) providing probabilistic detection of all use-after-free\n"
"                                    and inter-object overflows along with deterministic detection\n"
"                                    of all small/linear overflows and use-after-free until it has\n"
"                                    been reused once and gone through the quarantines twice"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:336
msgid ""
"On ARMv9, Branch Target Identification (BTI) and Pointer\n"
"                            Authentication Code (PAC) return address protection are enabled for\n"
"                            userspace OS code we build instead of only specific apps"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:339
msgid ""
"Signed integer overflow is made well defined in C and C++ for code\n"
"                            where automatic overflow checking is disabled"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:341
msgid ""
"\n"
"                                Hardened kernel\n"
"                                "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:344
msgid ""
"4-level page tables are enabled on arm64 to provide a much\n"
"                                    larger address space (48-bit instead of 39-bit) with\n"
"                                    significantly higher entropy Address Space Layout\n"
"                                    Randomization (33-bit instead of 24-bit)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:348
msgid ""
"Basic hardware memory tagging is used in the main kernel\n"
"                                    memory allocators (slab, page_alloc, non-executable vmalloc) to\n"
"                                    provide probabilistic detection of all use-after-free and\n"
"                                    inter-object overflows along with deterministic detection of\n"
"                                    use-after-free until the memory is allocated again (we plan to\n"
"                                    add deterministic detection of small/linear overflows like\n"
"                                    hardened_malloc)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:355
msgid ""
"Random canaries with a leading zero are added to the\n"
"                                    kernel heap (slub) to block C string overflows, absorb small\n"
"                                    overflows and detect linear overflows or other heap corruption\n"
"                                    when the canary value is checked (on free, copies to/from\n"
"                                    userspace, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:360
msgid ""
"Memory is wiped (zeroed) as soon as it's released in both\n"
"                                    the low-level kernel page allocator and higher level kernel\n"
"                                    heap allocator (slub). This substantially reduces the lifetime\n"
"                                    of sensitive data in memory, mitigates use-after-free\n"
"                                    vulnerabilities and makes most uninitialized data usage\n"
"                                    vulnerabilities harmless. Without our changes, memory that's\n"
"                                    released retains data indefinitely until the memory is handed\n"
"                                    out for other uses and gets partially or fully overwritten by\n"
"                                    new data."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:369
msgid ""
"In early boot, all the memory not being used by the OS is\n"
"                                    zeroed to get rid of any data leftover from a previous boot in\n"
"                                    case zero-on-free didn't have the opportunity to clear it as\n"
"                                    part of a clean reboot/shutdown. All the devices we support have\n"
"                                    a reset attack protection feature we proposed zeroing memory for\n"
"                                    firmware-based boot modes, but we need to finish it up by adding\n"
"                                    it for the OS boot modes ourselves. Fully encrypted RAM with a\n"
"                                    per-boot key cycled on reboots will eventually obsolete these\n"
"                                    features for newer devices."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:378
msgid ""
"Kernel stack allocations are zeroed to make most\n"
"                                    uninitialized data usage vulnerabilities harmless."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:380
msgid ""
"Assorted attack surface reduction through disabling\n"
"                                    features or setting up infrastructure to dynamically\n"
"                                    enable/disable them only as needed (perf, ptrace)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:383
msgid ""
"Assorted upstream hardening features are enabled,\n"
"                                    including many which we played a part in developing and\n"
"                                    landing upstream as part of our linux-hardened project (which\n"
"                                    we intend to revive as a more active project again)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:387
msgid ""
"Forced kernel module signing with per-build RSA 4096 and\n"
"                                    SHA256 keys, and lockdown mode set to forced confidentiality\n"
"                                    mode, help to enforce a low-level boundary between the kernel\n"
"                                    and userspace even if mistakes are made in SELinux policy or\n"
"                                    there's a deep userspace compromise."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:392
msgid ""
"Additional consistency/integrity checks are enabled for\n"
"                                    frequently targeted kernel data structures."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:394
msgid ""
"On ARMv9, Branch Target Identification (BTI) is enabled in\n"
"                                    addition to Clang type-based Control Flow Integrity (CFI) to\n"
"                                    cover functions excluded from type-based CFI"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:397
msgid ""
"On ARMv9, ShadowCallStack (SCS) is enabled in addition to\n"
"                                    Pointer Authentication Code (PAC) return address protection\n"
"                                    instead of only enabling SCS when PAC is unavailable"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:402
msgid ""
"Android Runtime Just-In-Time (JIT) compilation/profiling is fully\n"
"                            disabled and replaced with full ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation. The\n"
"                            only JIT compilation in the base OS is the V8 JavaScript JIT which is\n"
"                            disabled by default for the Vanadium browser with per-site exception\n"
"                            support."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:407
msgid ""
"Dynamic code loading for both native code or Java/Kotlin classes is\n"
"                            blocked for nearly the entire base OS. This works alongside verified\n"
"                            boot to prevent base OS processes from running attacker controlled\n"
"                            native code or Java/Kotlin code. The only exceptions from the policy for\n"
"                            the base OS are in-memory code loading for the media DRM sandbox and the\n"
"                            Vanadium JIT compiler being permitted. Vanadium has JIT compilation\n"
"                            disabled by default for every site and for apps using the WebView with\n"
"                            the exception of our PDF Viewer app. Vanadium disables the JIT compiler\n"
"                            by default with a per-site and per-app toggle for it and per-process\n"
"                            enforcement of blocking dynamic code loading implemented with\n"
"                            seccomp-bpf based on the per-site/per-app JIT compiler toggle."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:418
msgid ""
"Dynamic code loading for both native code or Java/Kotlin classes can\n"
"                            be disabled for user installed apps via 3 exploit protection toggles:\n"
"                            Dynamic code loading from memory, Dynamic code loading from storage and\n"
"                            WebView JIT. This can also be used to opt-out of the WebView JIT for our\n"
"                            PDF Viewer and dynamic code loading from memory for the Vanadium browser\n"
"                            to disable support for the per-site opt-in to JIT compilation. In order\n"
"                            to make the dynamic code loading toggles more usable, we show a user\n"
"                            facing notification when an app has dynamic code loading from memory or\n"
"                            storage blocked, including a file path being shown when it's blocked\n"
"                            from storage. This allows users to disable it for all their apps and\n"
"                            then enable them for the ones requiring it."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:429
msgid "Filesystem access hardening"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:433
msgid "Improved sandboxing"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:434
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS improves the app sandbox through hardening SELinux policy\n"
"                        and seccomp-bpf policy along with all the hardening to components like\n"
"                        kernel implementing the app sandbox and providing a path for the attacker\n"
"                        to escape it if they can exploit those components. We primarily focus on\n"
"                        the app sandbox, but we also improve the other sandboxes including making\n"
"                        direct improvements to the web browser renderer sandbox used for both the\n"
"                        default browser and WebView rendering engine provided by the OS and used\n"
"                        by a huge number of other apps from dedicated browsers to messaging\n"
"                        apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:445
msgid "Anti-persistence and detection"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:447
msgid "Enhanced "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:447
msgid "verified boot"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:447
msgid ""
"\n"
"                            with better security properties and reduced attack surface"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:449
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS finishes the incomplete implementation of verified boot\n"
"                            for out-of-band updates to packages (APKs) in the OS. We enforce this\n"
"                            by requiring fs-verity metadata signed with a trusted key for system\n"
"                            app updates both at install time and boot time. This provides\n"
"                            continuous verification where every read from an out-of-band APK\n"
"                            update is verified similarly to every read from a firmware, OS image\n"
"                            or APEX update being verified. The signing key and version are\n"
"                            enforced to prevent downgrades or other attacks such as replacing a\n"
"                            package with a variant of the same one from a different GrapheneOS\n"
"                            supported device. We disable the persistent package parsing cache to\n"
"                            prevent bypassing the metadata checks through this otherwise highly\n"
"                            persistent state, which only has a very small negative impact on boot\n"
"                            time from the data not being available from previous boots (typically\n"
"                            less than 1 second)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:463
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS closes a loophole where app-based system components\n"
"                            built as part of the OS can be downgraded to an older version due to\n"
"                            versionCode not being incremented when system components get updated\n"
"                            as part of changes to the OS. We enforce this both at package install\n"
"                            time and boot time."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:468
msgid ""
"Enhanced hardware-based attestation with more precise version information"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:469
msgid ""
"Hardware-based security verification and monitoring via our\n"
"                            "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:471
msgid ""
"Compressed APEX module support is disabled as it's not useful for GrapheneOS,\n"
"                            uses extra unnecessary storage space and adds more verified boot attack surface."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:478
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS includes fixes for a large number of vulnerabilities not yet\n"
"                    fixed in Android."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:480
msgid ""
"We're able to quickly and safely ship the latest Linux kernel LTS point\n"
"                    releases on devices with GKI (Generic Kernel Image) support including the 6th\n"
"                    and 7th generation Pixel phones. At the time of writing on 2023-11-06,\n"
"                    GrapheneOS is using the latest Linux 5.10 GKI LTS release (5.10.199) for 6th\n"
"                    and 7th generation Pixel phones. The stock Pixel OS is on Linux 5.10.157 from\n"
"                    2022-12-02 with a small number of additional patches backported. This means\n"
"                    GrapheneOS provides hundreds of relevant kernel patches including many\n"
"                    security patches not yet included in the stock OS. It's possible for us to\n"
"                    stay several months ahead due to their approach of moving to new LTS releases\n"
"                    only in quarterly releases after a long freeze and testing process."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:490
msgid ""
"We often find new vulnerabilities ourselves and report them upstream. We've\n"
"                    reported dozens of vulnerabilities for both the generic Android codebase and\n"
"                    also for Pixels specifically. We also often find missed patches which were\n"
"                    supposed to be included but were missed, especially when there are device\n"
"                    specific components with partially shared but separate codebases for different\n"
"                    devices."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:496
msgid ""
"Our overall approach is to focus on systemic privacy and security\n"
"                    improvements but fixing individual vulnerabilities is still very\n"
"                    important."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:502
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS has a compatibility layer providing the option to install and use\n"
"                    the official releases of Google Play in the standard app sandbox. Google Play\n"
"                    receives absolutely no special access or privileges on GrapheneOS as opposed to\n"
"                    bypassing the app sandbox and receiving a massive amount of highly privileged\n"
"                    access. Instead, the compatibility layer teaches it how to work within the full\n"
"                    app sandbox. It also isn't used as a backend for the OS services as it would be\n"
"                    elsewhere since GrapheneOS doesn't use Google Play even when it's installed."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:509
msgid ""
"Since the Google Play apps are simply regular apps on GrapheneOS, you install\n"
"                    them within a specific user or work profile and they're only available within that\n"
"                    profile. Only apps within the same profile can use it, and they need to explicitly\n"
"                    choose to use it. It works the same way as any other app and has no special\n"
"                    capabilities. As with any other app, it can't access data of other apps and\n"
"                    requires explicit user consent to gain access to profile data or the standard\n"
"                    permissions. Apps within the same profile can communicate with mutual consent and\n"
"                    it's no different for sandboxed Google Play."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:517
msgid ""
"Sandboxed Google Play is close to being fully functional and provides near\n"
"                    complete compatibility with the app ecosystem depending on Google Play. Only a\n"
"                    small subset of privileged functionality which we haven't yet ported to\n"
"                    different approaches with our compatibility layer is unavailable. Some\n"
"                    functionality is inherently privileged and can't be provided as part of the\n"
"                    compatibility layer."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:523
msgid ""
"The vast majority of Play services functionality works perfectly including\n"
"                    dynamically downloaded/updated modules (dynamite modules) and functionality\n"
"                    provided by modular app components such as Google Play Games. By default,\n"
"                    location requests are rerouted to a reimplementation of the Play geolocation\n"
"                    service provided by GrapheneOS. You can disable rerouting and use the standard\n"
"                    Play services geolocation service instead if you want the Google network\n"
"                    location service and related features."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:530
msgid ""
"Our compatibility layer includes full support for the Play Store. Play\n"
"                    Store services are fully available including in-app purchases, Play Asset\n"
"                    Delivery, Play Feature Delivery and app/content license checks. It can\n"
"                    install, update and uninstall apps with the standard approach requiring that\n"
"                    the user authorizes it as an app source and consents to each action. It will\n"
"                    use the standard Android 12+ unattended update feature to do automatic updates\n"
"                    for apps where it was the last installer."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:537
msgid ""
"usage guide\n"
"                    section on sandboxed Google Play"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:538
msgid " for instructions."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:542
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides an option to install and use the official releases of\n"
"                    Android Auto."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:544
msgid ""
"Android Auto requires privileged access in order to work. GrapheneOS uses\n"
"                    an extension of the sandboxed Google Play compatibility layer to make Android\n"
"                    Auto work with a reduced level of privileges."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:547 static/features.html:601 static/features.html:610
msgid "For more details, see the "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:547
msgid ""
"usage guide section\n"
"                    on Android Auto"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:552
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds a Network permission toggle for disallowing both direct and\n"
"                    indirect access to any of the available networks. The device-local network\n"
"                    (localhost) is also guarded by this permission, which is important for\n"
"                    preventing apps from using it to communicate between profiles. Unlike a\n"
"                    firewall-based implementation, the Network permission toggle prevents apps\n"
"                    from using the network via APIs provided by the OS or other apps in the same\n"
"                    profile as long as they're marked appropriately."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:559
msgid ""
"The standard INTERNET permission used as the basis for the Network\n"
"                    permission toggle is enhanced with a second layer of enforcement and proper\n"
"                    support for granting/revoking it on a per-profile basis."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:562
msgid ""
"To avoid breaking compatibility with Android apps, the added permission\n"
"                    toggle is enabled by default. However, the OS app installation UI has been\n"
"                    extended to show the toggle as part of the installation confirmation page so\n"
"                    users can disable it when installing an app."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:566
msgid ""
"When the Network permission is disabled, GrapheneOS pretends the network is\n"
"                    down. It shows the network as down in various APIs, returns errors showing a\n"
"                    network connectivity issue rather than a revoked permission and avoids running\n"
"                    scheduled jobs depending on the network. This results in apps handling it as\n"
"                    if the network is down rather than crashing or showing errors from trying to\n"
"                    use the network and being unable to do it."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:575
msgid ""
"Sensors permission toggle: disallow access to all other sensors not covered\n"
"                    by existing Android permissions (Camera, Microphone, Body Sensors, Activity\n"
"                    Recognition) including an accelerometer, gyroscope, compass, barometer,\n"
"                    thermometer and any other sensors present on a given device. When access is\n"
"                    disabled, apps receive zeroed data when they check for sensor values and don't\n"
"                    receive events. GrapheneOS creates an easy-to-disable notification when apps\n"
"                    try to access sensors blocked by the permission being denied. This makes the\n"
"                    feature more usable since users can tell if the app is trying to access this\n"
"                    functionality."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:584
msgid ""
"To avoid breaking compatibility with Android apps, the added permission is\n"
"                    enabled by default. When an app attempts to access sensors and receives zeroed\n"
"                    data due to being denied, GrapheneOS creates a notification that can be\n"
"                    easily disabled. The Sensors permission can be set to be disabled by default\n"
"                    for user installed apps in "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:588 static/features.html:704
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    Security &amp; privacy &gt;\n"
"                    More security &amp; privacy"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:594
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides Storage Scopes as a fully compatible alternative to the\n"
"                    standard Android storage permissions. Instead of granting storage permissions,\n"
"                    users can enable Storage Scopes to make the app assume that it has all storage\n"
"                    permissions that it asked for. On Android, an app that doesn't have any storage\n"
"                    permissions is still allowed to create files and directories, and is allowed to\n"
"                    access the files that it created. Users can optionally add files and directories\n"
"                    as storage scopes to permit the app to access files created by other apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:601
msgid ""
"usage guide\n"
"                    section on storage access"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:606
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides Contact Scopes as an alternative to granting the\n"
"                    Contacts permission. By default, it acts as if the contacts list is empty and\n"
"                    users can grant different kinds of access to specific contacts or groups of\n"
"                    contacts."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:610
msgid ""
"usage guide section\n"
"                    on Contact Scopes"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:615
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS has much broader carrier support than AOSP and mostly matches\n"
"                    the stock OS on Pixels without making the same sacrifices. We convert their\n"
"                    APN, carrier configuration, MMS and visual voicemail databases to the formats\n"
"                    used by AOSP with our CarrierConfig2 project and scripts. We strip out\n"
"                    anti-user configuration requiring provisioning for tethering, forbidding\n"
"                    disabling 2G, etc. We don't include the invasive carrier-specific apps and\n"
"                    support for Open Mobile Alliance Device Management (OMA DM) so we also strip\n"
"                    out configuration depending on those."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:623 static/features.html:646 static/features.html:765
msgid "See our "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:623
msgid ""
"usage guide section on\n"
"                    carrier functionality"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:628
msgid ""
" to reduce cellular radio\n"
"                    attack surface by disabling enormous amounts of both legacy code (2G, 3G) and\n"
"                    bleeding edge code (5G)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:634
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS supports per-connection MAC randomization and enables it by\n"
"                    default. This is a more private approach than the standard persistent\n"
"                    per-network random MAC used by modern Android."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:637
msgid ""
"When the per-connection MAC randomization added by GrapheneOS is being\n"
"                    used, DHCP client state is flushed before reconnecting to a network to avoid\n"
"                    revealing that it's likely the same device as before."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:640
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS also applies fixes for serious flaws with the Linux kernel IPv6\n"
"                    privacy address implementation which allow using it as an identifier not just\n"
"                    for connections to the same network but also across different networks. We\n"
"                    don't need to apply these changes for the Pixel 6 and later since this was\n"
"                    fixed in the Linux kernel upstream, but hasn't been backported to earlier\n"
"                    kernel LTS branches so we still need to take care of it there."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:646
msgid ""
"usage guide section on Wi-Fi privacy\n"
"                    for more general information"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:647
msgid ""
" rather than only our improvements to the\n"
"                    standard Wi-Fi privacy approach."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:652
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides network-based location as an opt-in feature with our own\n"
"                    implementation. Similar to the services provided by Apple and Google, it offers\n"
"                    location detection based on nearby networks rather than solely relying on using\n"
"                    satellite-based location (GNSS) with technologies to accelerate it (A-GNSS). It\n"
"                    makes getting a location indoors and in cities with tall buildings much faster\n"
"                    or possible when it wouldn't have worked via GNSS. Certain apps also have the\n"
"                    expectation of network-based location being available and don't account for the\n"
"                    time needed to get a GNSS-based estimate or inability to get one everywhere so\n"
"                    this feature provides improved compatibility with apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:661
msgid ""
"Unlike Google's service and similar to Apple's service, our feature provides\n"
"                    local position estimation based on retrieving location data for nearby networks\n"
"                    from a service. It caches the information from the service in-memory for up to\n"
"                    15 minutes from when it was last used so it can function offline after getting\n"
"                    the initial data. It only needs to send a network identifier for each network it\n"
"                    wants to use for position estimation. Google's service does server-side position\n"
"                    estimation which requires repeatedly sending distance estimates for each network\n"
"                    to the service for each position estimate update. The approach we use doesn't\n"
"                    require providing any information to the service once the nearby networks are in\n"
"                    the cache or sending distance estimates. The service also provides it with extra\n"
"                    data covering a fairly large area from the initial position with a reasonable\n"
"                    density of networks so it can keep functioning if internet access is lost."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:673
msgid ""
"Our network-based location feature is primarily based on Wi-Fi Access Points\n"
"                    (APs). Cell towers are used as a fallback when Wi-Fi-based location can't obtain\n"
"                    any position estimate. Apple and Google also use Bluetooth beacons but that's a\n"
"                    very niche feature only relevant to certain malls, stores, etc. which are\n"
"                    usually covered well enough by Wi-Fi support for decent position estimates so it\n"
"                    isn't a priority for us to add support for it."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:679
msgid ""
"Users can currently choose between using our proxy to Apple's service or\n"
"                    directly using Apple's service. We're in the process of building our own\n"
"                    database and service based on data from multiple sources including Apple's\n"
"                    service. Unlike the Apple and Google services, our service will provide support\n"
"                    for fully offline usage based on database downloads rather than requiring\n"
"                    sending network identifiers to the service to fetch data for them."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:685
msgid ""
"For details on how to use the network location feature, see the\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:686
msgid "usage section"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:690
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS disables the inclusion of sensitive metadata in screenshots."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:691
msgid ""
"On Android, each screenshot includes an EXIF Software tag with detailed OS\n"
"                    build/version information ("
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:692
msgid ""
"). It's the\n"
"                    same value shown at "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:693
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    About device &gt; Build number"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:694
msgid ""
". This\n"
"                    leaks the OS, OS version and also usually the device family/model since builds are\n"
"                    specific to a family of devices. GrapheneOS completely disables this\n"
"                    tag."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:698
msgid ""
"On Android, each screenshot also includes EXIF tags with the local date,\n"
"                    time and timezone offset. GrapheneOS disables this by default to\n"
"                    avoid leaking the time and quasi-location information through metadata that\n"
"                    isn't visible to the user. The date and time are already included in the file\n"
"                    name of the screenshot which is fully visible to the user and can be easily\n"
"                    modified by them without a third-party tool. GrapheneOS includes a toggle for\n"
"                    turning this metadata back on in "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:706
msgid " since some users may find it to be useful."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:710
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS fixes several prominent device identifier leaks bypassing\n"
"                    Android's intention of apps not being able to uniquely identify a device. See\n"
"                    our FAQ sections on "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:712
msgid ""
"hardware\n"
"                    identifiers"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:713
msgid ""
"non-hardware\n"
"                    identifiers"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:714
msgid " for more general information."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:715
msgid "secure application spawning system"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:715
msgid ""
"\n"
"                    primarily exists to significantly improve protection against exploitation.\n"
"                    However, it also improves privacy. On a device without our secure application\n"
"                    spawning system, the secrets used for probabilistic exploit mitigations such\n"
"                    as ASLR are usable as device identifiers persisting until reboot. This is an\n"
"                    easy way to identify the device from apps in different profiles. It's a minor\n"
"                    bonus of the feature and there are still plenty of side channels to identify\n"
"                    devices across apps, but it fixes most of the known direct identifier\n"
"                    leaks."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:724
msgid ""
"We also eliminate several holes in preventing apps from accessing hardware\n"
"                    identifiers including tightening up the restrictions for apps targeting legacy\n"
"                    Android platform versions."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:730
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS doesn't include or use Google apps and services by default and\n"
"                    avoids including any other apps/services not aligned with our privacy and\n"
"                    security focus. Google apps and services can be used on GrapheneOS as regular\n"
"                    sandboxed apps without any special access or privileges through our "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:733
msgid "sandboxed Google Play"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:733
msgid ""
" feature, but we don't\n"
"                    include those apps by default to give users an explicit choice on whether they\n"
"                    want to use those apps and which profiles they want to use it in."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:736
msgid ""
"We change the default settings to prefer privacy over small conveniences:\n"
"                    personalized keyboard suggestions based on gathering input history are\n"
"                    disabled by default, sensitive notifications are hidden on the lockscreen by\n"
"                    default and passwords are hidden during entry by default."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:740
msgid "Some of our changes for "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:740
msgid ""
"attack surface\n"
"                    reduction"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:741
msgid ""
" can also improve privacy by default by not exposing unnecessary\n"
"                    radios, etc. by default and avoiding the impact of potential privacy bugs with\n"
"                    the hardware."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:744
msgid ""
"By default, we also use GrapheneOS servers for the following services\n"
"                    instead of Google servers:"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:747
msgid "Connectivity checks"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:748
msgid "Attestation key provisioning"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:749
msgid "GNSS almanac downloads (PSDS) for Broadcom and Qualcomm (XTRA)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:750
msgid "Secure User Plane Location (SUPL)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:751
msgid "Network time"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:752
msgid "Vanadium (Chromium) component updates"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:754
msgid ""
"We provide a toggle to switch back to Google's servers for connectivity\n"
"                    checks, attestation key provisioning and GNSS almanac downloads along with\n"
"                    adding proper support for disabling network time connections. This combines\n"
"                    with other toggles to allow making a GrapheneOS device appear to be an AOSP\n"
"                    device. This is only particularly important for connectivity checks since the\n"
"                    other connections get routed through a VPN which is needed to blend in on a\n"
"                    local network in practice."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:761
msgid ""
"In addition to our SUPL privacy improvements, we override the SUPL server\n"
"                    to our proxy by default. We also add a toggle for users to switch to the\n"
"                    standard SUPL server for their carrier (usually supl.google.com) or disable it\n"
"                    entirely."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:765
msgid ""
"default connections FAQ entry\n"
"                    for much more detailed information"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:770
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds a toggle for enabling PIN scrambling to raise the\n"
"                    difficulty of figuring out the PIN being entered by a user either due to\n"
"                    physical proximity or a side channel. PIN scrambling is applied to both the\n"
"                    lock screen and SIM PIN/PUK."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:777
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds the option to require entering a 2nd factor PIN after\n"
"                    successfully authenticating with a fingerprint on the lockscreen in order to\n"
"                    complete unlocking the device. Since Android/iOS use biometric unlock as a\n"
"                    secondary unlock mechanism for convenience, this allows users to make use of a\n"
"                    strong passphrase as their primary unlock method with the convenience of a\n"
"                    fingerprint and short PIN for secondary unlock. Failure to enter the correct PIN\n"
"                    counts towards the standard attempt limit."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:786
msgid "Supports longer passwords"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:787
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS supports setting longer passwords by default: 128 characters\n"
"                    instead of 16 characters. This avoids the need to use a device manager to\n"
"                    enable this functionality."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:790
msgid ""
"This feature allows users to make use of diceware passwords if they don't\n"
"                    want to depend on the security of the secure element which provides very\n"
"                    aggressive throttling and offers a high level of security even for a random 6\n"
"                    digit PIN."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:797
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides an auto-reboot feature which reboots locked devices after\n"
"                    a set period of time to put data at rest. A countdown timer is started each time\n"
"                    the device is locked, and the device will reboot if a successful unlock doesn't\n"
"                    occur before the timer reaches zero. Unlocking any profile cancels the timer,\n"
"                    not just the Owner profile."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:802
msgid ""
"The timer is set to 18 hours by default, but can be set to values between 10\n"
"                    minutes and 72 hours, or turned off."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:804
msgid ""
"This feature doesn't apply when the device is in \"Before First Unlock\" state,\n"
"                    meaning that it will not lead to the device continuously rebooting, as data is\n"
"                    already at rest."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:807
msgid ""
"The feature is implemented in the init process, preventing it from being\n"
"                    bypassed through system process crashes since an init crash causes a kernel\n"
"                    panic which leads to a reboot."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:813
msgid "As documented in our section on "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:813
msgid ""
"our added\n"
"                    exploit mitigations"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:814
msgid ""
", GrapheneOS adds zeroing of freed memory to both the\n"
"                    standard userspace and kernel allocators. These features have the secondary\n"
"                    benefit of clearing sensitive data from memory as soon as possible in addition\n"
"                    to defending against exploits. Android implements regular compaction of frozen\n"
"                    cached apps and apps currently running in the background based on triggering a\n"
"                    full compacting garbage collection (GC) and then requesting that malloc frees as\n"
"                    much memory as it can back to the OS. This pairs well with zeroing features and\n"
"                    results in freed data getting cleared faster for Java/Kotlin and also the C, C++\n"
"                    and Rust libraries used by them where low-level allocators get held onto until\n"
"                    the high level objects are freed."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:824
msgid ""
"When the device is locked, we trigger full compacting garbage collection (GC)\n"
"                    for the SystemUI and system_server processes to release all of the memory that's\n"
"                    no longer used back to the OS. Due to GrapheneOS enabling kernel page allocator\n"
"                    zeroing, this results in all the no longer referenced data in objects being\n"
"                    cleared. We based our approach on Android's standard approach to running a full\n"
"                    compacting GC for these two processes after the device is unlocked to clear\n"
"                    remnants of the user's PIN/password and keys derived from it. This is a nice way\n"
"                    to clear some data immediately after locking prior to our\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:832
msgid "auto-reboot"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:832
msgid ""
" feature kicking in to clear all of the OS\n"
"                    memory."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:834
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS modifies some of the ways the device can be rebooted to proceed\n"
"                    with the normal reboot process where memory gets freed and cleared by the kernel\n"
"                    page and slab allocator zeroing features enabled by GrapheneOS."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:840
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides users with the ability to set a duress PIN/Password that\n"
"                    will irreversibly wipe the device (along with any installed eSIMs) once entered\n"
"                    anywhere where the device credentials are requested (on the lockscreen, along\n"
"                    with any such prompt in the OS)."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:844
msgid ""
"The wipe does not require a reboot and cannot be interrupted. It can be set\n"
"                    up at "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:845
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Security &amp; privacy &gt; Device unlock &gt; Duress Password"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:845
msgid ""
" in the owner profile. Duress\n"
"                    PIN is solely used for PIN entry and duress password is solely used for password\n"
"                    entry. Both a duress PIN and password are mandatory to enable the feature to\n"
"                    account for different profiles that may have different unlock methods. Duress\n"
"                    PIN will also wipe the device when entered as the\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:850
msgid "two-factor fingerprint unlock PIN"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:850
msgid ""
"\n"
"                    but not currently when entered as the SIM PIN."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:852
msgid ""
"Note that if the duress PIN/Password is the same as the actual unlock method,\n"
"                    the actual unlock method always takes precedence, and therefore no wipe will\n"
"                    occur."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:857
msgid "More secure fingerprint unlock"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:858
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS improves the security of the fingerprint unlock feature by only\n"
"                    permitting 5 total attempts rather than implementing a 30 second delay between\n"
"                    every 5 failed attempts with a total of 20 attempts. This doesn't just reduce\n"
"                    the number of potential attempts but also makes it easy to disable fingerprint\n"
"                    unlock by intentionally failing to unlock 5 times with a different finger."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:863
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS also adds support for using the fingerprint scanner only for\n"
"                    authentication in apps and unlocking hardware keystore keys by toggling off\n"
"                    support for unlocking. This feature already existed for the standard Android\n"
"                    face unlock feature."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:870
msgid ""
"Android's user profiles are isolated workspaces with their own instances of\n"
"                    apps, app data and profile data (contacts, media store, home directory, etc.).\n"
"                    Apps can't see the apps in other user profiles and can only communicate with\n"
"                    apps within the same user profile (with mutual consent with the other app).\n"
"                    Each user profile has their own encryption keys based on their lock method.\n"
"                    They're a great fit for GrapheneOS with a lot of room for improvement."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:876
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides improvements to user profile functionality and is\n"
"                    working on further improvements to make switching between them and monitoring\n"
"                    other profiles much more convenient."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:881
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS raises the limit on the number of secondary user profiles to 32\n"
"                        (31 + guest) instead of only 4 (3 + guest) to make this feature much more\n"
"                        flexible."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:887
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS also enables support for logging out of user profiles without\n"
"                        needing a device manager controlling the device to use this feature. Logging\n"
"                        out makes profiles inactive so none of the apps installed in them can run. It\n"
"                        also purges the disk encryption keys from memory and hardware registers,\n"
"                        putting the user profile back at rest."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:895
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds a toggle to the user management settings for disabling\n"
"                        secondary user app installation. You can install the apps you want to be\n"
"                        usable in a secondary user and then disable the ability to install more apps\n"
"                        as that user in the Owner profile. Android supports this as a standard device\n"
"                        management feature but doesn't make it available to a user who owns their own\n"
"                        device."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:903
msgid "Improved install available apps"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:904
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS enables the standard install available apps feature that's\n"
"                        still not enabled in AOSP or the stock Pixel OS to allow the Owner user to\n"
"                        install packages that are available in other users. This allows installing\n"
"                        an app in a secondary user that's already installed in the Owner user\n"
"                        without needing to download it again. This helps a lot with using the\n"
"                        toggles added for disabling app installation by secondary users."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:913
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS supports forwarding notifications from users running in the\n"
"                        background to the currently active user. Forwarding notifications to other\n"
"                        users is disabled by default and can be enabled within each user profile\n"
"                        where forwarding to the active profile is wanted. Notifications forwarded\n"
"                        from other profiles are displayed by default in a standard local\n"
"                        notification channel."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:922
msgid "GrapheneOS app repository"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:923
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS includes our own security, minimalism and usability-focused app\n"
"                    repository client for using our first-party app repository. Our app repository\n"
"                    is currently used to distribute our own apps and a mirror of Google Play for\n"
"                    the sandboxed Google Play feature. In the future, it will be used to\n"
"                    distribute first-party GrapheneOS builds of externally developed open source\n"
"                    apps with hardening applied."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:931
msgid "Vanadium: hardened WebView and default browser"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:932
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS includes our Vanadium browser as WebView implementation provided\n"
"                    by the OS and our default browser. Vanadium is a hardened variant of Chromium\n"
"                    providing enhanced privacy and security, similar to how GrapheneOS compares to\n"
"                    AOSP. The Vanadium browser currently doesn't add many features but there are a\n"
"                    lot of enhancements planned in the long term."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:937
msgid "Some of the features added compared to standard mobile Chromium:"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:939
msgid "Hardware memory tagging (MTE) enabled for the main allocator"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:940
msgid "Type-based Control Flow Integrity (CFI)"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:941
msgid "Strong stack protector"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:942
msgid "Automatic zero-initialized variables"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:943
msgid "Well-defined signed overflow"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:944
msgid "Strict site isolation and sandboxed iframes"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:945
msgid ""
"JavaScript JIT disabled by default with per-site toggle via drop-down\n"
"                        permission menu"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:947
msgid ""
"Enable support for the DrumBrake WebAssembly interpreter previously \n"
"                        exclusive to Microsoft Edge, to support WebAssembly when JIT compilation\n"
"                        is disabled"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:950
msgid ""
"Dynamic code execution is blocked for processes without the JavaScript\n"
"                        JIT enabled as an extension to the seccomp-bpf sandbox"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:952
msgid ""
"Native Android autofill implementation to avoid needing sandboxed Google\n"
"                        Play for autofill support"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:954
msgid ""
"Native Android credential manager support for passkeys to avoid needing\n"
"                        sandboxed Google Play for passkey support"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:956
msgid "WebGPU disabled for attack surface reduction"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:957
msgid "WebRTC IP handling policy toggle to control peer-to-peer WebRTC mode"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:958
msgid ""
"High performance content filtering engine using EasyList + EasyPrivacy\n"
"                        with per-site toggle via drop-down permission menu"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:960
msgid "More complete state partitioning without origin trial opt-out"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:961
msgid ""
"Standard Android 16 user agent reduction is enabled early for the\n"
"                        WebView to replace the major OS version, device model and browser\n"
"                        minor/build/patch version with standard placeholder values"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:964
msgid ""
"High entropy client hints are replaced with the standard placeholder\n"
"                        values used in Chromium's reduced user agent for both the browser and\n"
"                        WebView to close a loophole where Chromium is still sharing the major OS\n"
