#: static/features.html:1096
msgid ""
" with support for local backups and any cloud storage provider with a\n"
"                    storage provider app."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1098
msgid ""
"Seedvault was created by a GrapheneOS community member for inclusion in our\n"
"                    operating system. We plan on replacing it with a new implementation since the\n"
"                    project has been taken over by another group of people not sharing our goals\n"
"                    or approach. For now, this is the best available option, so we're including it\n"
"                    to give people encrypted backup support. We've made several security fixes to\n"
"                    work around upstream issues with the project."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1106
msgid "Location data access indicator"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1107
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS enables the privacy indicator for location data access in\n"
"                    addition to the standard Android camera and microphone indicators. This shows\n"
"                    an indicator when an app the user has granted permission to access location\n"
"                    requests location data. We also resolve various UX issues with this feature as\n"
"                    it currently exists in AOSP to get it into a highly usable state."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1112
msgid ""
"Android 13 has the location privacy indicator as a developer option but it\n"
"                    doesn't work the same way as it does in GrapheneOS. GrapheneOS shows it for\n"
"                    all location data accesses through any APIs. Normally, the stock OS only shows\n"
"                    it for GNSS location requests, also known as high power location requests, and\n"
"                    doesn't normally show it for network location and other APIs gated by the\n"
"                    Location permission and global block toggle."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1118
msgid ""
"The indicator works the same way as the Camera and Microphone ones, showing\n"
"                    a bright green icon when location access occurs which then gets minimized to a\n"
"                    small bright green dot when the quick settings tray isn't currently opened.\n"
"                    Android 12 already includes Location with the other standard runtime\n"
"                    permissions in the privacy dashboard for viewing the history."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1125
msgid "User installed apps can be disabled"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1126
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds support for disabling user installed apps instead of only\n"
"                    being able to disable system apps. This allows users to completely prevent one\n"
"                    of the apps they've installed from being able to run without being forced to\n"
"                    uninstall it and lose their app data. This is much stricter than the standard\n"
"                    force stop feature which only prevents an app from starting itself and the app\n"
"                    will start running again as soon as another app tries to open an activity or\n"
"                    service it provides."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1136
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS greatly improves Android's protection against VPN leaks for both\n"
"                    the built-in VPN support and VPN apps with the standard \"Block connections\n"
"                    without VPN\" toggle enabled."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1139
msgid ""
"Android allows DNS queries from the system resolver to leak to the network\n"
"                    provided DNS servers when a VPN app goes down due to a race condition. It also\n"
"                    similarly allows connections to the VPN DNS servers to happen outside of the VPN\n"
"                    tunnel. Both of these are fully prevented by GrapheneOS through extending the\n"
"                    leak blocking to this part of the system resolver, fully preventing unicast DNS\n"
"                    leaks."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1145
msgid ""
"Android allows processes including apps to bypass the VPN entirely whether\n"
"                    it's up or down by sending multicast packets either directly or by causing the\n"
"                    kernel to send the packets on their behalf through the standard multicast group\n"
"                    management system calls. GrapheneOS extends Android's standard eBPF filtering\n"
"                    with full support for blocking all forms of multicast packet bypasses. We also\n"
"                    disallow using the system Network Service Discovery Manager for connecting to\n"
"                    mDNS-based services when VPN lockdown is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1152
msgid ""
"Android VPN configuration is split up for each profile which means work\n"
"                    profiles, Private Spaces and secondary users have their own VPN configuration\n"
"                    which is a fantastic privacy feature. Android has a standard restriction\n"
"                    preventing processes from using a network which the current profile isn't\n"
"                    allowed to access. However, this doesn't take multicast packets into account and\n"
"                    it's possible to send multicast packets via VPN tunnels belonging to a different\n"
"                    profile. GrapheneOS addresses this by extending the standard netfilter\n"
"                    configuration with a multicast firewall preventing sending packets through a VPN\n"
"                    tunnel which a process isn't supposed to be able to access."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1161
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS closes a hole in Android's eBPF-based firewall system which made\n"
"                    it possible to bypass the VPN by specifying a specific interface with a special\n"
"                    system call."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1164
msgid ""
"Finding and resolving all forms of VPN leaks is one of our top priorities at\n"
"                    the moment and we don't currently consider this to be a complete feature due to\n"
"                    less severe additional issues we've discovered."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1170
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS adds a user-facing log viewer to the Settings app for Android's\n"
"                    standard in-memory logging system. The feature acts as a substitute for\n"
"                    automated crash reporting which is not implemented by GrapheneOS for privacy\n"
"                    reasons. Instead, users are in control of what's captured and shared. Our log\n"
"                    viewer supports filtering the output based on log level, log buffers and text\n"
"                    search. Users can copy, share or save the currently shown logs to a file. A\n"
"                    description can be added to document why the logs were captured."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1177
msgid "Overall system logs can be accessed at "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1177
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    System &gt; View logs"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1178
msgid ""
". Per-app logs can\n"
"                    be accessed at "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1179
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    Apps &gt; App name &gt; View logs"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1181
msgid ""
"We implement user-facing crash reporting tied to our log viewer for OS and\n"
"                    app crashes, greatly improving upon the very limited user-facing crash reporting\n"
"                    available in Android. This helps users report crashes to the OS or app\n"
"                    developers without requiring invasive automated crash reporting where users\n"
"                    don't control the data that's sent to developers."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1186
msgid ""
"Our user-facing crash reporting has special support for memory corruption\n"
"                    caught by hardened_malloc and hardware memory tagging informing users that\n"
"                    memory corruption was detected. Users choose how to proceed and whether it makes\n"
"                    sense to enable our compatibility toggles for the app if they don't believe it\n"
"                    was an exploit but rather an app bug they need to work around. It's a careful\n"
"                    balance between not encouraging users to disable security features protecting\n"
"                    user installed apps from exploits and making it easy to work around app bugs. We\n"
"                    don't allow disabling these exploit protection features for the base OS\n"
"                    including base OS apps, but too many user installed apps have latent memory\n"
"                    corruption bugs and we need to provide the option to work around them."
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1196
msgid "Users can enable more system crash reporting via "
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1196
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                    Security &amp; privacy &gt;\n"
"                    More security &amp; privacy &gt;\n"
"                    Notify about system process crashes"
msgstr ""

#: static/features.html:1199
msgid ""
". We don't enable reporting all kernel or\n"
"                    system process crashes by default since we can't manage triaging and\n"
"                    investigating every single Android OS bug causing a crash. We're focused on the\n"
"                    memory corruption crashes caught by hardware memory tagging so those are always\n"
"                    reported. Fixing every Android bug ourselves is not something we can hope to\n"
"                    accomplish so we focus our resources on the ones found by our improvements which\n"
"                    also have a higher chance of being security bugs."
msgstr ""

