#: static/usage.html:184
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS inherits the same baseline approach to storage access as modern\n"
"                Android and extends it with our Storage Scopes feature as a fully compatible\n"
"                alternative to standard Android storage permissions. This section provides an\n"
"                overview of the standard approach to storage access primarily to provide context\n"
"                for explaining Storage Scopes."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:189
msgid "There are two types of app-accessible storage:"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:191
msgid ""
"app-private (\"internal\") storage:\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:193
msgid "inaccessible to other apps"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:194
msgid "doesn't require any permission for full access"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:195
msgid "cleared when the app is uninstalled"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:198
msgid ""
"shared (\"external\") storage:\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:200
msgid "shared with other apps"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:201
msgid "access is regulated with permissions"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:202
msgid "files persist after uninstallation"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:203
msgid ""
"\n"
"                        Android/data/ and Android/obb/ directories aren't considered to be parts\n"
"                        of shared storage.\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:208
msgid ""
"For modern apps, access to the shared storage is controlled in the following"
" way:"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:210
msgid ""
"Without any storage permission, an app is allowed to:\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:212
msgid ""
"create media files in standard directories (audio in Music/,\n"
"                                Ringtones/, etc, images in Pictures/ and DCIM/, videos in DCIM/\n"
"                                and Movies/)"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:215
msgid ""
"create files of any type (both media and non-media) in Documents/\n"
"                                and Download/"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:217
msgid "create new directories inside standard directories"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:218
msgid "rename/delete files that were created by the app itself"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:219
msgid ""
"rename/delete directories if it can rename/delete all files within\n"
"                                those directories"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:223
msgid ""
"Media access permission (\"Allow access to media only\",\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:224
msgid ""
") allows the app to read media files\n"
"                        that were created by other apps. Non-media files remain invisible to it.\n"
"                        For apps targeting Android 13, the media access permission is split into\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:227
msgid ""
" and\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:229
msgid ""
"Media management special access permission (\"Allow app to manage media\",\n"
"                        "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:230
msgid ""
") allows the app to delete and to rename media\n"
"                        files created by other apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:232
msgid "\"All files access\" special access permission ("
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:232
msgid ""
")\n"
"                        allows the app to read, create, rename and delete files and directories\n"
"                        of any type in any directory of the shared storage (including the root\n"
"                        directory)."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:237
msgid ""
"For legacy apps (those that target Android 9 or lower and those that target\n"
"                Android 10 and request legacy storage mode), storage access permissions have\n"
"                a different meaning:"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:241
msgid ""
"Without a storage permission, app is not allowed any type of access to\n"
"                        any files or directories inside the shared storage."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:243
msgid ""
" permission allows the app to read both\n"
"                    media and non-media files in any directory."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:245
msgid ""
" permission allows the app to create,\n"
"                    rename and delete files (of any type) and directories in any directory of\n"
"                    shared storage (including the root directory)."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:249
msgid ""
"Additionally, both modern and legacy Android apps can open the system file\n"
"                picker interface to have the user store or load one or more files/directories on\n"
"                their behalf. This type of access doesn't require any of the permissions listed\n"
"                above. Using this approach gives the user control over where files are stored in\n"
"                their home directory and which files/directories can be used by the app. This is\n"
"                based on the Storage Access Framework (SAF) introduced in Android 4.4. SAF allows\n"
"                the user to grant access to files/directories in their home directory, external\n"
"                drives and also app-based storage providers such as network shares, cloud storage,\n"
"                an encrypted volume, an external drive with a filesystem the OS doesn't support\n"
"                for external drives, etc. This is the only way to use those app-based storage\n"
"                providers and modern Android has removed the legacy approach for accessing\n"
"                external drives."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:263
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides the Storage Scopes feature as a fully compatible alternative\n"
"                    to the standard Android storage permissions.\n"
"                    Storage Scopes can be enabled only if the app doesn't have any storage permission.\n"
"                    Enabling Storage Scopes makes the app assume that it has all of storage permissions\n"
"                    that were requested by it, despite not actually having any of them."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:268
msgid ""
"This means that the app can't see any of the files that were created by other apps.\n"
"                    The app is still allowed to create files and directories, same as any other modern\n"
"                    app that doesn't have any storage access permission."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:271
msgid ""
"Apps that would normally use the legacy storage mode are switched to the\n"
"                    modern storage mode when Storage Scopes is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:273
msgid ""
"If the app requests the \"All files access\" permission (or is a legacy app\n"
"                    that requests "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:274
msgid ""
" permission), then the write\n"
"                    restrictions that are normally applied to apps that don't have a storage access\n"
"                    permission are relaxed to provide the same write access that the app would have if\n"
"                    it was granted the \"All files access\" permission.\n"
"                    This is done to ensure compatibility with apps that, for example, create a new\n"
"                    directory in the root of shared storage, or write a text file (eg lyrics.txt) to\n"
"                    the Music/ directory (normally, only audio files can be placed there).\n"
"                    No additional read access is granted to such apps, they still can see only their\n"
"                    own files.\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:284
msgid ""
"For all other apps, enabling Storage Scopes doesn't grant any additional\n"
"                    storage access beyond what a modern app that doesn't have any storage permission\n"
"                    already has."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:287
msgid ""
"Optionally, users can specify which of the files created by other apps the app\n"
"                    can access. Access can be granted to a specific file or to all files in\n"
"                    a directory. The standard SAF picker is used for this purpose in a special mode\n"
"                    where it shows only shared storage files/directories."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:291
msgid ""
"The most significant limitation of Storage Scopes is the fact that the app\n"
"                    will lose access to files that it created if it's uninstalled and then installed\n"
"                    again, same as any other app that doesn't have a storage access permission.\n"
"                    As a workaround, users can manually grant access to these files/directories via\n"
"                    SAF picker."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:300
msgid ""
"On Android, contact access is controlled with an all-or-nothing Contacts permission, which grants\n"
"                both read and write access to all contacts stored on the device."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:302
msgid ""
"A lot of apps (e.g. popular messaging apps) refuse to work unless the "
"Contacts permission is granted."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:303
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS provides the Contact Scopes feature as an alternative to granting the Contacts permission.\n"
"                Enabling Contact Scopes makes the app assume that it has the Contacts permission, despite not actually \n"
"                having it. By default, an app that has Contact Scopes enabled is not allowed any kind of contact access."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:306
msgid "Optionally, read access can be granted to the following scopes:"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:308
msgid ""
"Contact data (phone number or email). Access to each type of number and email in a contact is\n"
"                    granted separately. Access to the contact name is granted automatically."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:310
msgid ""
"Single contact. Access is granted to all contact data, except contact photo."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:311
msgid ""
"Contact group (\"label\"). Equivalent to granting access to all contacts in the group. Any contact\n"
"                    can be in any number of contact groups."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:314
msgid ""
"The type and name of the account that the contact is stored in are fully hidden from the app. The name\n"
"                of the contact account is usually the same as the email address of that account."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:316
msgid ""
"When Contact Scopes is enabled, write access is fully blocked: the app is not allowed to edit any\n"
"                contact data, add or remove contacts, etc."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:321
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS includes all of the accessibility features from the Android Open\n"
"                Source Project and strives to fill in the gaps from not including Google apps and\n"
"                services. We include our own fork of the open source TalkBack accessibility\n"
"                service along with a Monochromacy option for the standard color correction\n"
"                menu."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:326
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS does not yet include a text-to-speech (TTS) service in the base OS\n"
"                due to limitations of the available options. Including one is planned in the\n"
"                future when a suitable option is available. RHVoice and eSpeak NG are both open\n"
"                source and are the most common choices by GrapheneOS users. Both of these work\n"
"                fine but have licensing issues. eSpeak NG has added Direct Boot based on our\n"
"                request for it, meaning it is able to function before the first unlock. RHVoice is\n"
"                missing Direct Boot and can't run before the first unlock. Installing and setting\n"
"                up either one of these or another TTS app will get TalkBack working. TalkBack\n"
"                itself supports Direct Boot and works before the first unlock but it needs to have\n"
"                a TTS app supporting it in order to do more than playing the activation sound\n"
"                before the first unlock. After installing a TTS service, you need to select it in\n"
"                the OS configuration to accept activating it. The OS will display one of them as\n"
"                already selected, but it won't simply work from being installed as that wouldn't\n"
"                be safe. This is the same as the stock OS but it comes with one set up\n"
"                already."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:341
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS disables showing the characters as passwords are typed by default. You\n"
"                can enable this in "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:342
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                Security &amp; privacy &gt; Privacy &gt; Show passwords"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:344
msgid ""
"Third party accessibility services can be installed and activated. This\n"
"                includes the ones made by Google. Most of these will work but some may have a hard\n"
"                dependency on functionality from Google Play services for some of their\n"
"                functionality or to run at all. Accessibility services are very powerful and we\n"
"                strongly recommend against using third party implementations if you can get by\n"
"                well without them. We plan to add safeguards in this area while still keeping them\n"
"                working without problematic barriers."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:354
msgid "tutorial page on the site for the attestation sub-project"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:358
msgid ""
"The update system implements automatic background updates. It checks for updates\n"
"                approximately once every six hours when there's network connectivity and then\n"
"                downloads and installs updates in the background. It will pick up where it left off if\n"
"                downloads are interrupted, so you don't need to worry about interrupting it.\n"
"                Similarly, interrupting the installation isn't a risk because updates are installed to\n"
"                a secondary installation of GrapheneOS which only becomes the active installation\n"
"                after the update is complete. Once the update is complete, you'll be informed with a\n"
"                notification and simply need to reboot with the button in the notification or via a\n"
"                normal reboot. If the new version fails to boot, the OS will be rolled back to the\n"
"                past version and the updater will attempt to download and install the update\n"
"                again."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:369
msgid ""
"The updater will use incremental (delta) updates to download only changes rather\n"
"                than the whole OS when one is available to go directly from the installed version to\n"
"                the latest version. As long as you have working network connectivity on a regular\n"
"                basis and reboot when asked, you'll almost always be on one of the past couple\n"
"                versions of the OS which will minimize bandwidth usage since incrementals will always\n"
"                be available."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:375
msgid ""
"The updater works while the device is locked and idle, including before the first\n"
"                unlock since it's explicitly designed to be able to run before decryption of user\n"
"                data."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:378
msgid "Release changelogs are available "
