#: static/usage.html:482
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS includes our Vanadium subproject providing privacy and security\n"
"                enhanced releases of Chromium. Vanadium is both the user-facing browser included\n"
"                in the OS and the provider of the WebView used by other apps to render web\n"
"                content. The WebView is the browser engine used by nearly all other apps embedding\n"
"                web content or using web technologies for other uses. It's also used by many minor\n"
"                web browsers not forking Chromium as a whole. These apps using the WebView benefit\n"
"                from a subset of the Vanadium hardening."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:489
msgid ""
"Vanadium was previously primarily focused on security hardening but we plan on\n"
"                adding assorted privacy and usability features. In the near future, we plan to add\n"
"                support for always incognito mode, improved state partitioning, backup/restore\n"
"                and many other features."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:493
msgid ""
"Chromium-based browsers like Vanadium provide the strongest sandbox\n"
"                implementation, leagues ahead of the alternatives. It is much harder to escape\n"
"                from the sandbox and it provides much more than acting as a barrier to\n"
"                compromising the rest of the OS. Site isolation enforces security boundaries\n"
"                around each site using the sandbox by placing each site into an isolated sandbox.\n"
"                It required a huge overhaul of the browser since it has to enforce these rules on\n"
"                all the IPC APIs. Site isolation is important even without a compromise, due to\n"
"                side channels. Browsers without site isolation are very vulnerable to attacks like\n"
"                Spectre. On mobile, due to the lack of memory available to apps, there are\n"
"                different modes for site isolation. Vanadium turns on strict site isolation,\n"
"                matching Chromium on the desktop, along with strict origin isolation."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:504
msgid ""
"Chromium has decent exploit mitigations, unlike the available alternatives.\n"
"                This is improved upon in Vanadium by enabling further mitigations, including those\n"
"                developed upstream but not yet fully enabled due to code size, memory usage or\n"
"                performance. For example, it enables type-based CFI like Chromium on the desktop,\n"
"                uses a stronger SSP configuration, zero initializes variables by default, etc.\n"
"                Some of the mitigations are inherited from the OS itself, which also applies to\n"
"                other browsers, at least if they don't do things to break them."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:511
msgid ""
"We recommend against trying to achieve browser privacy and security through\n"
"                piling on browser extensions and modifications. Most privacy features for browsers\n"
"                are privacy theater without a clear threat model and these features often reduce\n"
"                privacy by aiding fingerprinting and adding more state shared between sites. Every\n"
"                change you make results in you standing out from the crowd and generally provides\n"
"                more ways to track you. Enumerating badness via content filtering is not a viable\n"
"                approach to achieving decent privacy, just as AntiVirus isn't a viable way to\n"
"                achieving decent security. These are losing battles, and are at best a stopgap\n"
"                reducing exposure while waiting for real privacy and security features."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:520
msgid ""
"Vanadium will be following the school of thought where hiding the IP address\n"
"                through Tor or a trusted VPN shared between many users is the essential baseline,\n"
"                with the browser partitioning state based on site and mitigating fingerprinting to\n"
"                avoid that being trivially bypassed. The Tor Browser's approach is the only one\n"
"                with any real potential, however flawed the current implementation may be. This\n"
"                work is currently in a very early stage and it is largely being implemented\n"
"                upstream with the strongest available implementation of state partitioning.\n"
"                Chromium is using Network Isolation Keys to divide up connection pools, caches and\n"
"                other state based on site and this will be the foundation for privacy. Chromium\n"
"                itself aims to prevent tracking through mechanisms other than cookies, greatly\n"
"                narrowing the scope downstream work needs to cover. The focus is currently on\n"
"                research since we don't see much benefit in deploying bits and pieces of this\n"
"                before everything is ready to come together. At the moment, the only browser with\n"
"                any semblance of privacy is the Tor Browser but there are many ways to bypass the\n"
"                anti-fingerprinting and state partitioning. The Tor Browser's security is weak\n"
"                which makes the privacy protection weak. The need to avoid diversity\n"
"                (fingerprinting) creates a monoculture for the most interesting targets. This\n"
"                needs to change, especially since Tor itself makes people into much more of a\n"
"                target (both locally and by the exit nodes)."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:539
msgid ""
"WebView-based browsers use the hardened Vanadium rendering engine, but they can't\n"
"                offer as much privacy and control due to being limited to the capabilities supported\n"
"                by the WebView widget. For example, they can't provide a setting for toggling sensors\n"
"                access because the feature is fairly new and the WebView WebSettings API doesn't yet\n"
"                include support for it as it does for JavaScript, location, cookies, DOM storage and\n"
"                other older features. For sensors, the Sensors app permission added by GrapheneOS can\n"
"                be toggled off for the browser app as a whole instead. The WebView sandbox also\n"
"                currently runs every instance within the same sandbox and doesn't support site\n"
"                isolation."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:548
msgid ""
"Avoid Gecko-based browsers like Firefox as they're currently much more vulnerable\n"
"                to exploitation and inherently add a huge amount of attack surface. Gecko doesn't have\n"
"                a WebView implementation (GeckoView is not a WebView implementation), so it has to be\n"
"                used alongside the Chromium-based WebView rather than instead of Chromium, which means\n"
"                having the remote attack surface of two separate browser engines instead of only one.\n"
"                Firefox/Gecko also bypass or cripple a fair bit of the upstream and GrapheneOS\n"
"                hardening work for apps. Worst of all, Firefox does not have internal sandboxing\n"
"                on Android. This is despite the fact that Chromium semantic sandbox layer on\n"
"                Android is implemented via the OS "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:556
msgid ""
" feature, which is a\n"
"                very easy to use boolean property for app service processes to provide strong\n"
"                isolation with only the ability to communicate with the app running them via the\n"
"                standard service API. Even in the desktop version, Firefox's sandbox is still\n"
"                substantially weaker (especially on Linux) and lacks full support for isolating\n"
"                sites from each other rather than only containing content as a whole. The sandbox\n"
"                has been gradually improving on the desktop but it isn't happening for their\n"
"                Android browser yet."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:567
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS has the same camera capabilities and quality as the stock OS. It will\n"
"                match the stock OS when comparing the same app on each OS. GrapheneOS uses our own\n"
"                modern Camera app rather than the standard AOSP Camera app. On Pixels, Pixel Camera\n"
"                can be used as an alternative with more features. The section below has a detailed\n"
"                guide on using GrapheneOS Camera and the following section explains the remaining\n"
"                advantages of Pixel Camera on Pixels."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:575
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS includes our own modern camera app focused on privacy and\n"
"                    security. It includes modes for capturing images, videos and QR and barcode\n"
"                    scanning along with additional modes based on CameraX vendor extensions\n"
"                    (Portrait, HDR, Night, Face Retouch and Auto) on "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:578
msgid ""
"devices\n"
"                    where they're available"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:579
msgid " (Pixels currently only have support for Night mode)."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:580
msgid ""
"Modes are displayed as tabs at the bottom of the screen. You can switch\n"
"                    between modes using the tab interface or by swiping left/right anywhere on the\n"
"                    screen. The arrow button at the top of the screen opens the settings panel and\n"
"                    you can close it by pressing anywhere outside the settings panel. You can also\n"
"                    swipe down to open the settings and swipe up to close it. Outside of the QR\n"
"                    scanning mode, there's a row of large buttons above the tab bar for switching\n"
"                    between the cameras (left), capturing images and starting/stopping video\n"
"                    recording (middle) and opening the gallery (right). The volume keys can also\n"
"                    be used as an equivalent to pressing the capture button. While recording a\n"
"                    video, the gallery button becomes an image capture button for capturing\n"
"                    images."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:591
msgid ""
"Our Camera app provides the system media intents used by other apps to\n"
"                    capture images and record videos via the OS provided camera implementation.\n"
"                    These intents can only be provided by a system app since Android 11, so the\n"
"                    quality of the system camera is quite important."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:595
msgid ""
"The app has an in-app gallery and video player for images/videos taken with\n"
"                    it. It currently opens an external editor activity for the edit action.\n"
"                    GrapheneOS comes with AOSP Gallery which provides an editor activity. You can\n"
"                    install a nicer photo editor and the Camera app will be able to use it. We\n"
"                    plan to replace AOSP Gallery with a standalone variant of the gallery we're\n"
"                    developing for the Camera app in the future."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:601
msgid ""
"Using the default 4:3 aspect ratio for image capture is recommended since\n"
"                    16:9 is simply cropped output on all supported devices. A device oriented\n"
"                    towards video recording might actually have a wider image sensor but that's\n"
"                    not the case for Pixels or nearly any other smartphone."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:605
msgid ""
"Image capture uses lightweight HDR+ on all supported Pixels and HDRnet for the\n"
"                    preview on 5th generation Pixels. Using the torch or camera flash will result\n"
"                    in HDR+ being disabled which is why automatic flash isn't enabled by default.\n"
"                    The lightweight HDR+ doesn't use as many frames as the more aggressive Pixel\n"
"                    Camera HDR+. CameraX extensions will eventually provide support for an HDR\n"
"                    mode with more aggressive HDR+ taking/combining more than only around 3 frames.\n"
"                    It currently supports a Night mode providing the Night Sight variant of HDR+ inflating\n"
"                    the light of the scene through combining the frames. Other fancy features like\n"
"                    Portrait mode will also depend on CameraX extensions being provided in the\n"
"                    future. There isn't a timeline for when additional CameraX extensions will be added."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:615
msgid ""
"Zooming via pinch to zoom or the zoom slider will automatically make use of\n"
"                    the wide angle and telephoto cameras on Pixels. 5th and 6th generation Pixels\n"
"                    (4a (5G), 5, 5a, 6, 6 Pro) have a wide angle camera for zooming out to under\n"
"                    1x to capture a much wider field of view. Images taken with the wide angle\n"
"                    lens won't match the quality of the normal camera, especially with 6th\n"
"                    generation Pixels. Flagship 4th generation Pixels (4, 4 XL) have a telephoto\n"
"                    camera providing 2x optical zoom and the Pixel 6 Pro has one providing 4x\n"
"                    optical zoom."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:623
msgid ""
"By default, continuous auto focus, auto exposure and auto white balance are\n"
"                    used across the whole scene. Tapping to focus will switch to auto focus, auto\n"
"                    exposure and auto white balance based on that location. The focus timeout\n"
"                    setting determines the timeout before it switches back the default mode. The\n"
"                    exposure compensation slider on the left allows manually tuning exposure and\n"
"                    will automatically adjust shutter speed, aperture and ISO without disrupting\n"
"                    lightweight HDR+ support. Further configuration and tuning will be provided in\n"
"                    the future."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:631
msgid ""
"The QR scanning mode only scans within the scanning square marked on the\n"
"                    screen. The QR code should be aligned with the edges of the square but can\n"
"                    have any 90 degree orientation. Non-standard inverted QR codes are fully\n"
"                    supported. It's a very quick and high quality QR scanner able to easily scan\n"
"                    very high density QR codes from Pixels. Every 2 seconds, it will refresh auto\n"
"                    focus, auto exposure and auto white balance on the scanning square. It has\n"
"                    full support for zooming in and out. The torch can be toggled with the button\n"
"                    at the bottom center. The auto toggle at the bottom left can be used to toggle\n"
"                    scanning for all supported barcode types. Alternatively, you can select which\n"
"                    barcode types it should scan via the menu at the top. It only scans QR codes\n"
"                    by default since that provides quick and reliable scanning. Most other types\n"
"                    of barcodes can result in false positives. Each enabled type will slow down\n"
"                    the scanning and will make it more prone to false positives especially with\n"
"                    difficult to scan barcodes such as a dense QR code."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:645
msgid ""
"Camera permission is the only one that's required. Images and videos are\n"
"                    stored via the Media Store API so media/storage permissions aren't required.\n"
"                    The Microphone permission is needed for video recording by default but not\n"
"                    when including audio is disabled. Location permission is only needed if you\n"
"                    explicitly enabling location tagging."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:650
msgid ""
"By default, EXIF metadata is stripped for captured images and only includes\n"
"                    the orientation. Stripping metadata for videos is planned but not supported\n"
"                    yet. Orientation metadata isn't stripped since it's fully visible from how the\n"
"                    image is displayed so it doesn't count as hidden metadata and is needed for\n"
"                    proper display. You can toggle off stripping EXIF metadata in the More\n"
"                    Settings menu opened from the settings dialog. Disabling metadata stripping\n"
"                    will leave the timestamp, phone model, exposure configuration and other\n"
"                    metadata. Location tagging is disabled by default and won't be stripped if you\n"
"                    enable it."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:659
msgid ""
"Electronic Image Stabilization (EIS) is enabled by default on devices\n"
"                    providing it via the Camera2 API and can be disabled using the video settings\n"
"                    dialog."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:662
msgid ""
"Zero Shutter Lag (ZSL) is available as an opt-in toggle in More Settings\n"
"                    and speeds up image capture for the Camera mode when flash is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:667
msgid ""
"Pixel Camera (previously known as Google Camera) can take full advantage of the\n"
"                    available cameras and image processing hardware as it can on the stock OS and does\n"
"                    not require GSF or sandboxed Google Play on GrapheneOS. Direct TPU and GXP access\n"
"                    by Google apps including Pixel Camera is controlled by a toggle added by GrapheneOS\n"
"                    and doesn't provide them with any additional access to data. The toggle exists for\n"
"                    attack surface reduction. Every app can use the TPU and GXP via standard APIs\n"
"                    including the Android Neural Networks API and Camera2 API regardless."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:674
msgid ""
"We aim to reduce the benefits of Pixel Camera compared to GrapheneOS\n"
"                    Camera over time, especially on Pixels. Many features of Pixel Camera will\n"
"                    end up being available for GrapheneOS Camera in the next year or so via\n"
"                    CameraX extensions including more aggressive HDR+, Night Sight and Portrait.\n"
"                    Video features such as slow motion and time lapse are likely further away than\n"
"                    within the next year. These video features could potentially be provided via\n"
"                    CameraX vendor extensions or could be implemented via our own post-processing\n"
"                    of the video output. Panorama, Photo Sphere, Astrophotography, Motion Photos,\n"
"                    Frequent Faces, Dual Exposure Controls, Google Lens, etc. aren't on the\n"
"                    roadmap for GrapheneOS Camera. Video frame rate configuration and H.265\n"
"                    support should be available for GrapheneOS Camera in the near future via\n"
"                    CameraX improvements along with DNG (RAW) support in the further future."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:690
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS creates fresh processes (via exec) when spawning applications instead of\n"
"                using the traditional Zygote spawning model. This improves privacy and security at the\n"
"                expense of higher cold start app spawning time and higher initial memory usage. It\n"
"                doesn't impact runtime performance beyond the initial spawning time. It adds somewhere\n"
"                in the ballpark of 200ms to app spawning time on the flagship devices and is only very\n"
"                noticeable on lower-end devices with a weaker CPU and slower storage. The spawning\n"
"                time impact only applies when the app doesn't already have an app process and the OS\n"
"                will try to keep app processes cached in the background until memory pressure forces\n"
"                it to start killing them."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:699
msgid ""
"In the typical Zygote model, a template app process is created during boot and\n"
"                every app is spawned as a clone of it. This results in every app sharing the same\n"
"                initial memory content and layout, including sharing secrets that are meant to be\n"
"                randomized for each process. It saves time by reusing the initialization work. The\n"
"                initial memory usage is reduced due to copy-on-write semantics resulting in memory\n"
"                written only during initialization being shared between app processes."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:705
msgid ""
"The Zygote model weakens the security provided by features based on random secrets\n"
"                including Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR), stack canaries, heap canaries,\n"
"                randomized heap layout and memory tags. It cripples these security features since\n"
"                every app has the values for every other app and the values don't change for fresh app\n"
"                processes until reboot. Much of the OS itself is implemented via non-user-facing apps\n"
"                with privileges reserved for OS components. The Zygote template is reused across user\n"
"                profiles, so it also provides a temporary set of device identifiers across profiles\n"
"                for each boot via the shared randomized values."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:713
msgid "This feature can be disabled via "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:713
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                Security &amp; privacy &gt;\n"
"                Exploit protection &gt; Secure app spawning"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:715
msgid ""
"\n"
"                if you prefer to have faster cold start app spawning time and lower app process\n"
"                memory usage instead of the substantial security benefits and the removal of the\n"
"                only known remaining direct device identifiers across profiles (i.e. not depending\n"
"                on fingerprinting global configuration, available storage space, etc. or using side\n"
"                channels)."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:724
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS substantially expands the standard mitigations for memory corruption\n"
"                vulnerabilities. Some of these features are designed to directly catch the memory\n"
"                corruption bugs either via an explicit check or memory protection and abort the\n"
"                program in order to prevent them from being exploited. Other features mitigate issues\n"
"                a bit less directly such as zeroing data immediately upon free, isolated memory\n"
"                regions, heap randomization, etc. and can also lead to latent memory corruption bugs\n"
"                crashing instead of the program continuing onwards with corrupted memory. This means\n"
"                that many latent memory corruption bugs in apps are caught along with some in the OS\n"
"                itself. These bugs are not caused by GrapheneOS, but rather already existed and are\n"
"                uncovered by the features. The features are aimed at preventing or hindering exploits,\n"
"                not finding bugs, but they do that as part of doing their actual job."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:735
msgid ""
"Similarly, some of the other privacy and security improvements reduce the access\n"
"                available to applications and they may crash. Some of these features are always\n"
"                enabled under the hood, while others like the Network and Sensors toggles are\n"
"                controlled by users via opt-in or opt-out toggles. Apps may not handle having access\n"
"                taken away like this, although it generally doesn't cause any issues as it's all\n"
"                designed to be friendly to apps and fully compatible rather than killing the\n"
"                application when it violates the rules."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:742
msgid ""
"You can enable our exploit protection compatibility mode via\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:743 static/usage.html:1127
msgid "Settings &gt; Apps &gt; "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:743 static/usage.html:1127
msgid "APP"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:743
msgid ""
" &gt;\n"
"                Exploit protection compatibility mode"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:744
msgid ""
". The exploit protection compatibility mode\n"
"                toggle will:"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:747
msgid "Switch from hardened_malloc to Android's standard allocator (Scudo)"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:748
msgid "Reduce address space size from 48 bit to Android's standard 39 bit"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:749
msgid ""
"Disable memory tagging, unless the app has opted-in to it (only on\n"
"                        compatible devices)"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:751
msgid "Allow native debugging (ptrace) access"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:753
msgid ""
"All of these changes apply only to the selected app and can be toggled "
"separately."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:754
msgid ""
"If you run into an application aborting, try to come up with a process for\n"
"                reproducing the issue and then capture a bug report via the 'Take bug report'\n"
"                feature in Developer options. Report an issue to "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:756
msgid ""
"the GrapheneOS OS\n"
"                issue tracker"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:757
msgid " and email the bug report capture zip to "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:757
msgid ""
" with the\n"
"                issue tracker number in the subject like \"Bug report capture for issue\n"
"                #104\". The bug report capture includes plain text 'tombstones' with logs,\n"
"                tracebacks, address space layout, register content and a tiny bit of context\n"
"                from memory from areas that are interesting for debugging.  This may contain\n"
"                some sensitive data. Feel free to provide only the tombstone for the relevant\n"
"                crash and filter out information you don't want to send. However, it will be\n"
"                more difficult to debug if you provide less of the information. If the app\n"
"                doesn't work with sensitive information, just send the whole tombstone."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:769
msgid ""
"Wi-Fi on GrapheneOS is very privacy-friendly and is essentially anonymous as long\n"
"                as apps do not leak uniquely identifying information to the network. GrapheneOS avoids\n"
"                allowing itself to be fingerprinted as GrapheneOS, other than connections which are\n"
"                documented (see the "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:772
msgid "default connections FAQ"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:772
msgid ""
")\n"
"                and can be easily disabled or forced through a VPN service."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:776
msgid ""
"MAC randomization is always performed for Wi-Fi scanning. Pixel\n"
"                    phones have firmware support for scanning MAC randomization going\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:778
msgid "significantly beyond a naive implementation"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:778
msgid ""
".\n"
"                    On many other devices, there are identifiers exposed by Wi-Fi scanning beyond the MAC\n"
"                    address such as the packet sequence number and assorted identifying information in the\n"
"                    probe requests."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:782
msgid ""
"Avoid using hidden APs (i.e. APs not broadcasting their SSID) since all\n"
"                    known hidden SSIDs end up being broadcast as part of scanning for networks to\n"
"                    find them again. SSIDs are not broadcast for standard non-hidden APs. Hidden\n"
"                    APs are only hidden when no devices are connected. It makes little sense as a\n"
"                    privacy feature, especially for a non-mobile AP where knowing the AP exists\n"
"                    can't be used for tracking it since it doesn't move. The feature reduces your\n"
"                    privacy rather than increasing it. If you need to use a hidden AP, make sure\n"
"                    to delete the saved network afterwards."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:790
msgid ""
"Wi-Fi and Bluetooth scanning for improving location detection are disabled by\n"
"                    default, unlike the stock OS. These can be toggled in "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:791
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Location &gt;\n"
"                    Location services &gt; Wi-Fi and Bluetooth\n"
"                    scanning"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:793
msgid ""
". These features enable scanning even when Wi-Fi or Bluetooth is\n"
"                    disabled, so these need to be kept disabled to fully disable the radios when\n"
"                    Wi-Fi and Bluetooth are disabled. GrapheneOS itself doesn't currently include a\n"
"                    supplementary location service based on Wi-Fi and Bluetooth scanning. These\n"
"                    options impact whether apps such as sandboxed Google Play are able to use the\n"
"                    functionality if you grant them the Location permission. GrapheneOS plans to\n"
"                    eventually include an OS service based on local databases rather than a\n"
"                    network-based service giving the user's location to a server whenever location\n"
"                    is being used."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:805
msgid ""
"Associated MAC randomization is performed by default. This can be controlled\n"
"                    per-network in "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:806
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Network\n"
"                    &amp; internet &gt; Internet &gt; "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:807
msgid "NETWORK"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:807
msgid " &gt; Privacy"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:808
msgid ""
"In the stock OS, the default is to use a unique persistent random MAC address for\n"
"                    each network. It has 2 options available: \"Use randomized MAC (default)\" and \"Use\n"
"                    device MAC\". In GrapheneOS, the default is generating a new random MAC address when\n"
"                    connecting to a network. It has 3 options available: \"Use per-connection randomized MAC\n"
"                    (default)\", \"Use per-network randomized MAC\" and \"Use device MAC\"."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:813
msgid ""
"In rare cases, broken routers are unable to accept new clients once their\n"
"                    DHCP table is full instead of clearing the last recently used entry. You can\n"
"                    work around this by manually clearing the DHCP table via the router\n"
"                    administration page and can switch to the per-network randomized MAC mode to\n"
"                    avoid triggering the issue again. This would prevent a router being used in\n"
"                    any situation where many clients naturally come and go even without\n"
"                    per-connection MAC randomization and is not generally an issue for any modern\n"
"                    routers. Per-connection MAC randomization only makes it more likely to find a\n"
"                    one of the rare routers with this issue."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:822
msgid ""
"The DHCP client uses the anonymity profile rather than sending a hostname\n"
"                    so it doesn't compromise the privacy offered by MAC randomization. When the\n"
"                    per-connection MAC randomization added by GrapheneOS is being used, DHCP\n"
"                    client state is flushed before reconnecting to a network to avoid revealing\n"
"                    that it's likely the same device as before."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:827
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS also disables support for stable link-local IPv6 addresses, since these\n"
"                    have the potential to be used as identifiers. It's more sensible to use typical\n"
"                    link-local address generation based on the (randomized) MAC address since link-local\n"
"                    devices have access to both. As of Android 11, Android only uses stable link-local\n"
"                    privacy addresses when MAC randomization is disabled, so we no longer need to disable\n"
"                    the feature."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:837
msgid ""
"For more information on the network location feature and how it works, see the\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:838
msgid "features section"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:839
msgid "The setting can be found at "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:839
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                Location &gt; Location services &gt; Network location"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:840
msgid ""
". The available options are using\n"
"                Apple's network location service, or a GrapheneOS proxy to that service."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:842
msgid ""
"To use this feature, you need to make sure that you either have Wi-Fi enabled, or that\n"
"                Wi-Fi scanning is enabled at "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:843
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                Location &gt; Location services &gt; Wi-Fi scanning"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:844
msgid ""
", or you have cell reception (far less accurate).\n"
"                Enabling the Wi-Fi scanning setting will allow you to use Wi-Fi-based network location even if\n"
"                you disable the global Wi-Fi toggle."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:850
msgid ""
"If you have a reliable LTE connection from your carrier, you can reduce attack\n"
"                surface by disabling 2G, 3G and 5G connectivity in "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:851
msgid ""
"Settings &gt; Network &amp; internet &gt;\n"
"                SIMs &gt; "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:852 static/usage.html:1193 static/usage.html:1225
msgid "SIM"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:852
msgid " &gt; Preferred network type"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:852
msgid ""
". Traditional voice calls will only\n"
"                work in the LTE-only mode if you have either an LTE connection and VoLTE (Voice over LTE) support or\n"
"                a Wi-Fi connection and VoWi-Fi (Voice over Wi-Fi) support. VoLTE and VoWi-Fi works on GrapheneOS for\n"
"                most carriers unless they restrict it to carrier phones. Some carriers may be missing VoWi-Fi due to\n"
"                us not including their proprietary apps. Please note that AT&amp;T users may see \"5Ge\" being used\n"
"                when LTE Only mode is enabled as AT&amp;T intentionally mislabel LTE services as \"5Ge\" to mislead\n"
"                users."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:859
msgid ""
"This feature is not intended to improve the confidentiality of traditional calls and\n"
"                texts, but it might somewhat raise the bar for some forms of interception. It's not a\n"
"                substitute for end-to-end encrypted calls and texts or even transport layer encryption.\n"
"                LTE does provide basic network authentication and encryption, but it's for the network\n"
"                itself. The intention of the LTE-only feature is only hardening against remote\n"
"                exploitation by disabling an enormous amount of both legacy code (2G, 3G) and bleeding\n"
"                edge code (5G)."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:871
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS has a compatibility layer providing the option to install and use\n"
"                the official releases of Google Play in the standard app sandbox. Google Play\n"
"                receives absolutely no special access or privileges on GrapheneOS as opposed to\n"
"                bypassing the app sandbox and receiving a massive amount of highly privileged\n"
"                access. Instead, the compatibility layer teaches it how to work within the full\n"
"                app sandbox. It also isn't used as a backend for the OS services as it would be\n"
"                elsewhere since GrapheneOS doesn't use Google Play even when it's installed."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:878
msgid ""
"Since the Google Play apps are simply regular apps on GrapheneOS, you install\n"
"                them within a specific user or work profile and they're only available within that\n"
"                profile. Only apps within the same profile can use it and they need to explicitly\n"
"                choose to use it. It works the same way as any other app and has no special\n"
"                capabilities. As with any other app, it can't access data of other apps and\n"
"                requires explicit user consent to gain access to profile data or the standard\n"
"                permissions. Apps within the same profile can communicate with mutual consent and\n"
"                it's no different for sandboxed Google Play."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:886
msgid ""
"Sandboxed Google Play is close to being fully functional and provides near\n"
"                complete compatibility with the app ecosystem depending on Google Play. Only a\n"
"                small subset of privileged functionality which we haven't yet ported to different\n"
"                approaches with our compatibility layer is unavailable. Some functionality is\n"
"                inherently privileged and can't be provided as part of the compatibility\n"
"                layer."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:892
msgid ""
"The vast majority of Play services functionality works perfectly including\n"
"                dynamically downloaded and updated modules (dynamite modules) and functionality\n"
"                provided by modular app components such as Google Play Games. By default, location\n"
"                requests are rerouted to a reimplementation of the Play geolocation service\n"
"                provided by GrapheneOS. You can disable rerouting and use the standard Play\n"
"                services geolocation service instead if you want the Google network location\n"
"                service and related features. This shouldn't be needed outside of testing or\n"
"                obscure use cases, since GrapheneOS provides its own opt-in\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:900
msgid "Network Location"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:900 static/usage.html:970
msgid " feature."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:901
msgid ""
"Our compatibility layer includes full support for the Play Store. Play Store\n"
"                services are fully available including in-app purchases, Play Asset Delivery, Play\n"
"                Feature Delivery and app and content license checks. It can install, update and\n"
"                uninstall apps with the standard approach requiring that the user authorizes it as\n"
"                an app source and consents to each action. It will use the standard Android 12+\n"
"                unattended update feature to do automatic updates for apps where it was the last\n"
"                installer."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:910
msgid ""
"The simplest approach is to only use the Owner user profile. Apps installed\n"
"                    in the Owner profile are sandboxed the same way as everywhere else and don't\n"
"                    receive any special access. If you want to choose which apps use Google Play\n"
"                    rather than making it available to all of them, install it in a separate user\n"
"                    or work profile for apps depending on Google Play. You could also do it the\n"
"                    other way around, but it makes more sense to try to use as much as possible\n"
"                    without Google Play rather than treating not using it as the exceptional\n"
"                    case."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:918
msgid ""
"To install sandboxed Google Play, open our App Store, select Google Play\n"
"                    services and install it. This will install both Google Play services and Google\n"
"                    Play Store which are interdependent. Existing installs of sandboxed Google Play\n"
"                    from before Android 15 will also have Google Services Framework installed and it\n"
"                    shouldn't be removed."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:923
msgid ""
"Google Play services and Google Play Store are updated through the App Store.\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:925
msgid ""
"You should give a battery optimization exception to Google Play services\n"
"                    for features like push notifications to work properly in the background. It\n"
"                    isn't needed for the Google Play Store app."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:928
msgid ""
"Signing in into a Google account is optional, unless you want to\n"
"                    use features depending on being signed into an account. For example, some apps\n"
"                    use Google account authentication instead of their accounts having a username\n"
"                    and password. The Play Store requires being signed into an account in order to\n"
"                    install apps or use in-app purchases. This is still true even for an alternate\n"
"                    frontend to the Play Store. Aurora Store still requires an account but fetches\n"
"                    shared account credentials from Aurora Store's service by default."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:935
msgid ""
"The Play Store provides many services used by apps including Play Asset\n"
"                    Delivery, Play Feature Delivery, in-app purchases and license checks for paid\n"
"                    apps. The Play Store app is also the most secure way to install and update apps\n"
"                    from the Play Store."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:939
msgid ""
"Our compatibility layer has support for Play Games Services which you can\n"
"                    obtain by installing Google Play Games from the Play Store. Many games on the\n"
"                    Play Store depend on having Google Play Games installed."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:945
msgid ""
"The compatibility layer has a configuration menu available at\n"
"                    "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:946
msgid "Settings &gt; Apps &gt; Sandboxed Google Play"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:947
msgid ""
"By default, apps using Google Play geolocation are redirected to our own\n"
"                    implementation on top of the standard OS geolocation service. You don't need to\n"
"                    grant any permissions to Google Play or change any settings for working location\n"
"                    in apps using Google Play geolocation due to our rerouting feature."
