#: static/usage.html:1079
msgid ""
"Banking apps are a particularly problematic class of apps for compatibility\n"
"                with alternate operating systems. Some of these work fine with any GrapheneOS\n"
"                configuration but most of them have extensive dependencies on Play services. For\n"
"                many of these apps, it's enough to set up the GrapheneOS sandboxed Google Play\n"
"                feature in the same profile. Unfortunately, there are further complications not\n"
"                generally encountered with non-financial apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1085
msgid ""
"Many of these apps have their own crude anti-tampering mechanisms trying to\n"
"                prevent inspecting or modifying the app in a weak attempt to hide their code and API\n"
"                from security researchers. GrapheneOS allows users to disable "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1087
msgid ""
"Native code\n"
"                debugging"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1088
msgid " via a toggle in "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1088
msgid ""
"Settings &gt;\n"
"                Security &amp; privacy &gt; Exploit protection"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1089
msgid ""
"\n"
"                to improve the app sandbox and this can interfere with apps debugging their\n"
"                own code to add a barrier to analyzing the app. You should try enabling this again if you've\n"
"                disabled it and are encountering compatibility issues with these kinds of apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1093
msgid ""
"Banking apps are increasingly using Google's SafetyNet attestation service to\n"
"                check the integrity and certification status of the operating system. GrapheneOS\n"
"                passes the "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1095
msgid ""
" check but isn't certified by Google so it\n"
"                fails the "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1096
msgid ""
" check. Most apps currently only enforce\n"
"                weak software-based attestation which can be bypassed by spoofing what it checks.\n"
"                GrapheneOS doesn't attempt to bypass the checks since it would be very fragile and\n"
"                would repeatedly break as the checks are improved. Devices launched with Android 8\n"
"                or later have hardware attestation support which cannot be bypassed without leaked\n"
"                keys or serious vulnerabilities so the era of being able to bypass these checks by\n"
"                spoofing results is coming to an end regardless."
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1103
msgid ""
"The hardware attestation feature is part of the Android Open Source Project and\n"
"                is fully supported by GrapheneOS. SafetyNet attestation chooses to use it to\n"
"                enforce using Google certified operating systems. However, app developers can use\n"
"                it directly and permit other properly signed operating systems upholding the\n"
"                security model. GrapheneOS has a\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1108
msgid "detailed guide"
msgstr ""

#: static/usage.html:1108
msgid ""
" for app\n"
"                developers on how to support GrapheneOS with the hardware attestation API. Direct\n"
"                use of the hardware attestation API provides much higher assurance than using\n"
"                SafetyNet so these apps have nothing to lose by using a more meaningful API and\n"
"                supporting a more secure OS."
msgstr ""

