#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:37
msgid ""
"Apps using the Play Integrity API or the\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:38
msgid "obsolete"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:38
msgid ""
"\n"
"            SafetyNet Attestation API to check the authenticity/integrity of the OS, can support\n"
"            GrapheneOS by using the standard Android hardware attestation API instead and\n"
"            permitting our official release signing keys. Android's\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:42
msgid ""
"hardware\n"
"            attestation API"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:43
msgid ""
" provides a much stronger form of attestation than the Play\n"
"            Integrity API with the ability to whitelist the keys of alternate operating systems.\n"
"            It also avoids an unnecessary dependency on Google Play services and Google's\n"
"            Play Integrity servers."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:47
msgid ""
"The standard hardware attestation API can be used to verify the authenticity/integrity\n"
"            of the hardware, firmware, OS and the app running on it. It provides a verified boot key\n"
"            fingerprint for the OS for permitting secure aftermarket operating systems. The app ID,\n"
"            signing key fingerprint(s) and version code of the app enabling hardware attestation are\n"
"            included in the signed public key certificate for the generated key. This enables the\n"
"            app's service to make sure the app is genuine and unmodified along with chaining trust\n"
"            through the OS to the app which can sign messages with the attested hardware keystore\n"
"            key to prove they come from their app running on top of a verified OS, firmware and\n"
"            hardware. The only practical way to bypass hardware attestation is through exploiting\n"
"            the hardware keystore to obtain attestation signing keys, which is protected against by\n"
"            the ability to revoke keys that are being misused. Play Integrity API strong integrity\n"
"            level is directly based on the hardware key attestation API, but apps using it directly\n"
"            can support aftermarket operating systems, check the hardware attested OS patch level\n"
"            and other provided information. The hardware attestation API also supports pinning-based\n"
"            security instead of only root-based security where keys can be leaked and used to fake\n"
"            attestations. Apps can use pinning to establish a much higher security pairing with a\n"
"            specific device to obtain fresh attestations with a very high level security based on\n"
"            the security of the device's own hardware keystore rather than the overall ecosystem.\n"
"            Hardware attestation also doesn't require using any Google service beyond regularly\n"
"            fetching the list of revoked keys for root-based attestation. The app's service doesn't\n"
"            have to go down or start permitting anything if the Google services becomes unavailable\n"
"            or blocks the app from using it for one reason or another. Using hardware attestation is\n"
"            therefore more reliable and lower risk for apps."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:70
msgid ""
"Devices have been required to ship with hardware attestation support since Android\n"
"            8. You can use hardware attestation on devices running Android 8 or later when the\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:72
msgid ""
" system property isn't set to 25 or below,\n"
"            which indicates they launched with Android 8 or later with hardware attestation\n"
"            support as a mandatory feature. On older devices, you can continue using the Play\n"
"            Integrity API. Some low quality devices shipped broken implementations of hardware\n"
"            attestation despite the requirement to have it working for CDD/CTS certification and\n"
"            the Play Integrity API currently still passes on those devices wrongly claiming them\n"
"            to be CTS certified. If you don't want to fail on those devices, then you can start\n"
"            with hardware attestation and fall back to the Play Integrity API or do both and\n"
"            accept either passing as success."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:81
msgid "Google provides a "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:81
msgid ""
"key\n"
"            attestation library"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:82
msgid " with examples. Our "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:82
msgid ""
"MIT\n"
"            and Apache 2 licensed Auditor app"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/attestation-compatibility-guide.html:83
msgid ""
" can be used as a reference implementation for\n"
"            verifying hardware-based attestations. There are some subtleties in the verification\n"
"            process such as making sure only the 2nd certificate in the chain (the one signing the\n"
"            certificate for the key generated by your app) has an attestation extension to prevent\n"
"            making a fake attestation by extending the chain. You can reuse our code and simply\n"
"            omit support for an app generated attestation signing key (attest key) and the other\n"
"            pinning support."
msgstr ""

