#: static/articles/positon-location-service.html:6
msgid "Positon location service | Articles | GrapheneOS"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/positon-location-service.html:36
msgid "Positon location service"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/positon-location-service.html:37
msgid ""
"The Positon location service is a proprietary and highly privacy invasive service\n"
"            created by developers tied to /e/OS with their funding. There's a deliberate effort to\n"
"            hide that it's tied to them in order to convince other projects to adopt it, as opposed\n"
"            to using the similar service they host for /e/OS itself. Using the service requires\n"
"            uploading sensitive location data to obtain location estimates, similar to the Apple and\n"
"            Google location services. As with the Apple and Google services, it's a centralized\n"
"            proprietary service with fully proprietary data. Unlike those services, the people\n"
"            behind it have a history of publishing notoriously insecure software such as the /e/OS\n"
"            operating system itself which massively rolls back standard security, lags years behind\n"
"            on security updates and covers all of that up. They blatantly scam their users with\n"
"            false privacy/security claims for /e/OS, and nothing different should be expected from a\n"
"            location service from the same group of people. Multiple people involved in it are also\n"
"            actively participating in harassment targeting privacy/security researchers and\n"
"            engineers including but not limited to GrapheneOS team members."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/positon-location-service.html:51
msgid ""
"The people behind the Positon location service have repeatedly talked about the\n"
"            importance they see in centralizing the whole open source community around using their\n"
"            service while locking out alternatives to it through proprietary data. They have spread\n"
"            fear, uncertainty and doubt about making services using open mapping data through\n"
"            claiming that it's a privacy hazard for people to have access to maps of Wi-Fi networks\n"
"            publicly broadcasting their SSID despite that data already being available through many\n"
"            commercial providers including publicly queryable databases such as Wigle. Anyone can\n"
"            drive around building these maps and many companies have already built them, with the\n"
"            data available for sale, as Positon shows with them obtaining access to it. The real\n"
"            privacy hazard is sending your location in real time to a service, particularly a poorly\n"
"            secured one from people known to cover up and downplay vulnerabilities. Positon has been\n"
"            built to grab as much market share as possible early on before actual open options can\n"
"            emerge and gather the necessary data."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/positon-location-service.html:64
msgid ""
"The people involved in Positon have only ever cared about their careers, power and\n"
"            influence. They've consistently been on a side against real privacy and security, but\n"
"            rather focused on monetizing people's demand for it and grabbing as much market share as\n"
"            they can as quickly as they can with endless false marketing and attacks on projects\n"
"            like GrapheneOS. They see GrapheneOS as a huge threat to them due to us striving to\n"
"            bring people real privacy and security at no cost, which is far easier to obtain and\n"
"            use. This invalidates the business model of their companies like Murena. They\n"
"            consistently use their non-profits mainly as a way to earn money and promote their\n"
"            for-profit initiatives."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/positon-location-service.html:73
msgid ""
"The service claims to be free of charge, but a core goal is turning it into a way to\n"
"            get data from users to build their own database that's largely not going to be available\n"
"            for use by others. Using it is helping them build a future business at the expense of\n"
"            user privacy, little different from the Apple and Google services. This is not what the\n"
"            open source community needs from a location service. The claims of no strings attached\n"
"            and the implication that it's open are nonsense. Storing as little data as possible\n"
"            would mean using local database for the region, not a network-based service. They're\n"
"            opposed to doing a local service well rather than it being their long term goal. They\n"
"            explicitly aim to lock out other alternatives and deter local location detection via\n"
"            Wi-Fi."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:6
msgid "Server traffic shaping | Articles | GrapheneOS"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:37
msgid ""
"This article covers implementing server traffic shaping on Linux with CAKE. The aim\n"
"            is to provide fair usage of bandwidth between clients and consistently low latency\n"
"            for dedicated and virtual servers provided by companies like OVH and others."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:40
msgid ""
"Traffic shaping is generally discussed in the context of a router shaping traffic\n"
"            for a local network with assorted clients connected. It also has a lot to offer on a\n"
"            server where you don't control the network. If you control your own infrastructure\n"
"            from the server to the ISP, you probably want to do this on the routers instead."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:44
msgid ""
"This article was motivated by the serious lack of up-to-date information on this\n"
"            topic elsewhere. It's very easy to implement on modern Linux kernels and the results\n"
"            are impressive from extremely simple test cases to heavily loaded servers."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:48
msgid "Problem"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:49
msgid ""
"A server will generally be provisioned with a specific amount of bandwidth\n"
"                enforced by a router in close proximity. This router acts as the bottleneck and\n"
"                ends up being in charge of most of the queuing and congestion decisions. Unless\n"
"                that's under your control, the best you can hope for is that the router is\n"
"                configured to use "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:53
msgid ""
" as the queuing discipline (qdisc) to\n"
"                provide fair queuing between streams and low latency by preventing a substantial\n"
"                backlog of data."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:56
msgid "Unfortunately, the Linux kernel still defaults to "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:56
msgid ""
"\n"
"                instead of the much saner "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:57
msgid ""
" algorithm. This is changed by a\n"
"                configuration file shipped with systemd, so "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:58
msgid "most"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:58
msgid ""
" distributions using\n"
"                systemd as init end up with a sane default. Debian removes that configuration and\n"
"                doesn't set a sane default itself, and is widely used. Many server providers like\n"
"                OVH do not appear to consistently use modern queue disciplines like\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:62
msgid ""
" within their networks, particularly at artificial\n"
"                bottlenecks implementing rate limiting based on product tiers."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:64
msgid ""
"If the bottleneck doesn't use fair queuing, division of bandwidth across\n"
"                streams is very arbitrary and latency suffers under congestion. These issues are\n"
"                often referred to as bufferbloat, and "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:66
msgid ""
" is quite good at\n"
"                resolving it."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:68
msgid ""
" algorithm is far from perfect. It has issues with\n"
"                hash collisions and more importantly only does fair queuing between streams.\n"
"                Buffer bloat also isn't the only relevant issue. Clients with multiple connections\n"
"                receive more bandwidth and a client can open a large number of connections to\n"
"                maximize their bandwidth usage at the expense of others. Fair queuing is important\n"
"                beyond as a solution to bufferbloat and there's more to fair queuing than doing it\n"
"                only based on streams."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:75
msgid ""
"Traditionally, web browsers open a bunch of HTTP/1.1 connections to each server\n"
"                which ends up giving them an unfair amount of bandwidth. HTTP/2 is much friendlier\n"
"                since it uses a single connection to each server for the entire browser. Download\n"
"                managers take this to the extreme and intentionally use many connections to bypass\n"
"                server limits and game the division of resources between clients."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:82
msgid "Solution"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:83
msgid ""
"Linux 4.19 and later makes it easy to solve all of these problems. The CAKE\n"
"                queuing discipline provides sophisticated fair queuing based on destination and\n"
"                source addresses with finer-grained fairness for individual streams."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:86
msgid ""
" Unfortunately, simply enabling it as your queuing discipline isn't enough\n"
"                since it's highly unlikely that your server is the network bottleneck. You need to\n"
"                configure it with a bandwidth limit based on the provisioned bandwidth to move the\n"
"                bottleneck under your control where you can control how traffic is queued."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:92
msgid "Results"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:93
msgid ""
"We've used an 100mbit OVH server for as a test platform for a case where\n"
"                clients can easily max out the server bandwidth on their own. As a very simple\n"
"                example, consider 2 clients with more than 100mbit of bandwidth each downloading a\n"
"                large file. These are (rounded) real world results with CAKE:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:98
msgid "client A with 1 connection gets 50mbit"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:99
msgid "client B with 10 connections gets 5mbit each adding up to 50mbit"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:101
msgid "CAKE with "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:101
msgid " instead of the default "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:101
msgid ""
" to\n"
"                mimic "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:102
msgid " at a bottleneck:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:104
msgid "client A with 1 connection gets 9mbit"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:105
msgid "client B with 10 connections gets 9mbit each adding up to 90mbit"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:107
msgid ""
"The situation without traffic shaping is a mess. Latency takes a serious hit\n"
"                that's very noticeable via SSH. Bandwidth is consistently allocated very unevenly\n"
"                and ends up fluctuating substantially between test runs. The connections tend to\n"
"                settle near a rate, often significantly lower or higher than the fair 9mbit\n"
"                amount. It's generally something like this, but the range varies a lot:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:113
msgid "client A with 1 connection gets ~6mbit to ~14mbit"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:114
msgid ""
"client B with 10 connections gets ~6mbit to ~14mbit each adding up to ~86mbit\n"
"                    to ~94mbit"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:117
msgid ""
"CAKE continues working as expected with a far higher number of connections. It\n"
"                technically has a higher CPU cost than "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:118
msgid ""
", but that's much more\n"
"                of a concern for low end router hardware. It hardly matters on a server, even one\n"
"                that's under heavy CPU load. The improvement in user experience is substantial and\n"
"                it's very noticeable in web page load speeds when a server is under load."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:124
msgid "Implementation"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:125
#, python-format
msgid ""
"For a server with 2000mbit of bandwidth provisioned, you could start by trying\n"
"                it with 99.75% of the provisioned bandwidth:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:128
#, python-format
msgid ""
"On a server, setting it to use 100% of the provisioned bandwidth may work fine\n"
"                in practice. Unlike a local network connected to a consumer ISP, you shouldn't\n"
"                need to sacrifice anywhere close to the typically recommended 5-10% of your\n"
"                bandwidth for traffic shaping."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:132
msgid "The flow isolation mode is set to "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:132
msgid ""
" for fairness over\n"
"                destination addresses and then over individual flows. The default of\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:134
msgid ""
" uses a hash based on both destination and source\n"
"                addresses for host isolation which is counterproductive for this server use\n"
"                case."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:137
msgid "This also sets "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:137
msgid ""
" for the common case where the server\n"
"                doesn't have appropriate Quality of Service markings set up via Diffserv. Fair\n"
"                scheduling is already great at providing low latency by cycling through the hosts\n"
"                and streams without needing this kind of configuration. The defaults for Diffserv\n"
"                traffic classes like real-time video are set up to yield substantial bandwidth in\n"
"                exchange for lower latency. It's easy to set this up wrong and it usually won't\n"
"                make much sense on a server. You might want to set up marking low priority traffic\n"
"                like system updates, but it will already get a tiny share of the overall traffic\n"
"                on a loaded server due to fair scheduling between hosts and streams."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:146
msgid "You can use the "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:146
msgid " command to monitor CAKE:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:148
msgid "If you want to keep an eye on how it changes over time:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:150
msgid ""
"This is very helpful for figuring out if you've successfully moved the\n"
"                bottleneck to the server. If the bandwidth is being fully used, it should\n"
"                consistently have a backlog of data where it's applying the queuing discipline.\n"
"                The backlog shouldn't be draining to near zero under full bandwidth usage as that\n"
"                indicates the bottleneck is the server application itself or a different network\n"
"                bottleneck."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:156
msgid ""
"If you use systemd-network, you can add a CAKE configuration section to the\n"
"                network configuration file instead of manually running the "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:157
msgid ""
" command\n"
"                with a "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:158
msgid " service on boot:"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:165
msgid "Quicker backpressure propagation"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:166
msgid ""
"The Linux kernel can be tuned to more quickly propagate TCP backpressure up to\n"
"                applications while still maximizing bandwidth usage. This is incredibly useful for\n"
"                interactive applications aiming to send the freshest possible copy of data and for\n"
"                protocols like HTTP/2 multiplexing streams/messages with different priorities over\n"
"                the same TCP connection. This can also substantially reduce memory usage for TCP\n"
"                by reducing buffer sizes closer to the optimal amount for maximizing bandwidth\n"
"                use without wasting memory. The downside to quicker backpressure propagation is\n"
"                increased CPU usage from additional system calls and context switches."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:174
msgid ""
"The Linux kernel automatically adjusts the size of the write queue to maximize\n"
"                bandwidth usage. The write queue is divided into unacknowledged bytes (TCP window\n"
"                size) and unsent bytes. As acknowledgements of transmitted data are received, it\n"
"                frees up space for the application to queue more data. The queue of unsent bytes\n"
"                provides the leeway needed to wake the application and obtain more data. This can\n"
"                be reduced using "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:179
msgid ""
" to reduce the default and\n"
"                the "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:180
msgid " socket option to override it per-socket."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:181
msgid ""
"A reasonable choice for internet-based workloads concerned about latency and\n"
"                particularly prioritization within TCP connections but unwilling to sacrifice\n"
"                throughput is 128kiB. To configure this, set the following in\n"
"                "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:184
msgid ""
" or another sysctl configuration file and\n"
"                load it with "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:185 static/install/cli.html:180
#: static/install/cli.html:326 static/install/cli.html:337
msgid ":"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:187
msgid ""
"Using values as low as 16384 can make sense to further improve latency and\n"
"                prioritization. However, it's more likely to negatively impact throughput and will\n"
"                further increase CPU usage. Use at least 128k or the default of not limiting the\n"
"                automatic unsent buffer size unless you're going to do substantial testing to make\n"
"                sure there's not a negative impact for the workload."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:192
msgid "If you decide to use "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:192
msgid ""
", be aware that newer Linux\n"
"                kernels (Linux 5.0+ with a further improvement for Linux 5.10+) are recommended to\n"
"                substantially reduce system calls and context switches by not triggering the\n"
"                application to provide more data until over half the unsent byte buffer is\n"
"                empty."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:199
msgid "High link speed"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:200
msgid ""
"By default, CAKE splits General Segmentation Offload (GSO) super-packets to\n"
"                reduce latency at the expense of CPU efficiency and throughput. This can create a\n"
"                bottleneck at high link speeds. We've had to disable this on the 2Gbit GrapheneOS\n"
"                update servers."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:211
msgid "Future"
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:212
msgid ""
"Ideally, data centers would deploy CAKE throughout their networks with the\n"
"                default "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:213
msgid ""
" flow isolation. This may mean they need to use\n"
"                more powerful hardware for routing. If the natural bottlenecks used CAKE, setting\n"
"                up traffic shaping on the server wouldn't be necessary. This doesn't seem likely\n"
"                any time soon. Deploying "
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/server-traffic-shaping.html:216
msgid ""
" is much more realistic and tackles\n"
"                buffer bloat but not the issue of fairness between hosts rather than only\n"
"                streams."
msgstr ""

#: static/articles/sitewide-advertising-industry-opt-out.html:6
