#: static/history/copperheados.html:36
msgid "CopperheadOS is now GrapheneOS"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:37
msgid ""
"CopperheadOS was renamed to GrapheneOS in 2019. It was temporarily known as the\n"
"            Android Hardening project in 2018 before a permanent name had been chosen. For more\n"
"            details on why the project was renamed, see "
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:39
msgid "our history page"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:39
msgid ""
".\n"
"            For the historical release notes of the original CopperheadOS, see\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:41
msgid "our legacy changelog page"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:41
msgid ""
". The\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:42
msgid "/r/CopperheadOS subreddit"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:42
msgid ""
" was\n"
"            historically the central hub of the community along with a bridged IRC/Matrix channel\n"
"            that's no longer available."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:45
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS is the continuation of the original open source project by the original\n"
"            development team. Our "
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:46
msgid "source code repositories"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:46
msgid ""
" have been used\n"
"            since CopperheadOS transitioned to being directly based on the Android Open Source\n"
"            Project in 2015. The prior repositories predate the CopperheadOS branding and were\n"
"            also owned by us. It can be confirmed that our repositories are the original ones from\n"
"            the GitHub network graphs showing the forks over the years."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:52
msgid "Ownership"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:53
msgid ""
"We own the historical CopperheadOS source code, documentation and accounts tied\n"
"                to the open source project. Our legacy Twitter account still needs to be returned\n"
"                to us so that it can be renamed and made into an archive."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:56
msgid ""
"Copperhead has no valid claim over the ownership of the source code. It was not\n"
"                developed for them. They were involved as a sponsor for the work and had\n"
"                permission to sell products based on it, similar to companies selling devices with\n"
"                GrapheneOS. We've learned a lot of lessons from what happened and are being very\n"
"                careful to avoid being strongly associated with any particular company in the\n"
"                future."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:64
msgid "New closed source product reusing the legacy branding"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:65
msgid ""
"The new product branded as CopperheadOS is closed source and not associated with\n"
"                the original project. They took our project's previous name and copied our legacy\n"
"                source code and documentation. Attribution to us has been stripped away and they\n"
"                pretend to be the ones who created it."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:69
msgid ""
"They've essentially stolen the identity of our open source project and have\n"
"                invested substantial resources into misrepresenting GrapheneOS as being a new\n"
"                project. They've built a business based on taking credit for research and\n"
"                development not done by them. Substantial damage has been done to GrapheneOS\n"
"                through an organized campaign of misinformation and harassment."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:76
msgid "New CopperheadOS vs. GrapheneOS"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:77
msgid ""
"The new CopperheadOS is a shadow of the historical GrapheneOS code. They've\n"
"                continued copying portions of our newer generation code but haven't developed any\n"
"                significant privacy or security improvements on their own. It's a poor imitation\n"
"                of the original. It has a fraction of the privacy and security improvements and\n"
"                lacks a team with an understanding of how they work. It often doesn't receive\n"
"                timely security updates. It has made serious mistakes compromising user privacy\n"
"                and security."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:84
msgid ""
"CopperheadOS is a paid product and has license enforcement compromising user\n"
"                privacy and security through tracking devices to implement DRM. They use the\n"
"                outrageous business model of charging users for security updates rather than\n"
"                simply selling them the software or devices with it."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:88
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS devices can be purchased from a bunch of different companies,\n"
"                organizations and individuals. Many of these offer customer support. Unlike\n"
"                CopperheadOS, it's still open source software and you aren't being charged to\n"
"                simply get the OS updates. Anyone can sell devices with GrapheneOS without\n"
"                permission from the project due the open source licensing. Many of these sellers\n"
"                voluntarily contribute back to the project."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/copperheados.html:94
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS is far more actively developed than the new CopperheadOS and has\n"
"                substantially more resources available, including significantly more funding."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:6
msgid "History | GrapheneOS"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:39
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS was founded by Daniel Micay in late 2014. It started as a solo project\n"
"            incorporating his previous open source privacy/security work. The project initially\n"
"            created a port of OpenBSD malloc to Android's Bionic libc and a port of the PaX kernel\n"
"            patches to the kernels for the supported devices. It quickly expanded to having a\n"
"            large set of homegrown privacy and security improvements, particularly low-level\n"
"            hardening work on the compiler toolchain and Bionic. Work began on landing code\n"
"            upstream in AOSP and other upstream projects. A substantial portion of these early\n"
"            changes were either successfully landed upstream or heavily influenced the upstream\n"
"            changes which replaced them. The project was able to move very quickly in these days\n"
"            because there was so much low hanging fruit to address and it wasn't yet trying to\n"
"            produce a highly robust, production quality OS."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:50
msgid ""
"In late 2015, a company was incorporated which became the primary sponsor of the\n"
"            project. GrapheneOS was "
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:51
msgid ""
"previously known as\n"
"            CopperheadOS"
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:52
msgid ""
" while it was sponsored by this company. The intention was to use the\n"
"            company to build a business around GrapheneOS selling support, contract work and\n"
"            customized proprietary variants of the OS. The company was supposed to serve the needs\n"
"            of the open source project, rather than vice versa. It was explicitly agreed that\n"
"            GrapheneOS would remain independently owned and controlled by Daniel Micay. This\n"
"            company failed to live up the promises and is no longer associated in any way with\n"
"            GrapheneOS. The company ended up holding back the open source project and taking far\n"
"            more from it than was provided to it."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:60
msgid ""
"In 2018, the company was hijacked by the CEO who attempted to take over the project\n"
"            through coercion, but they were rebuked. They seized the infrastructure and stole the\n"
"            donations, but the project successfully moved on without them and has been fully\n"
"            revived. Since then, they've taken to fraudulently claiming ownership and authorship\n"
"            of our work, which has no basis in fact. They've tried to retroactively change the\n"
"            terms of their involvement and rewrite the history of the project. These claims are\n"
"            easily disproven through the public record and by people involved with the open source\n"
"            project and the former sponsor. This former sponsor has engaged in a campaign of\n"
"            misinformation and harassment of contributors to the project. Be aware that they are\n"
"            actively trying to sabotage GrapheneOS and are engaging in many forms of attacks\n"
"            against the project, the developers, contributors and supporters. Meanwhile, they\n"
"            continue profiting from our open source work which they falsely claim as their own\n"
"            creation."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:73
msgid ""
"After splitting from the former sponsor, the project was rebranded to\n"
"            AndroidHardening and then to GrapheneOS and it has continued down the original path of\n"
"            being an independent open source project. It will never again be closely tied to any\n"
"            particular sponsor or company."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:77
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS now has multiple full-time and part-time developers supported by\n"
"            donations and multiple companies collaborating with the project."
msgstr ""

#: static/history/index.html:79
msgid ""
"GrapheneOS Foundation was created as a non-profit organization in Canada in March\n"
"            2023 to handle the intake and distribution of donations."
msgstr ""

