#~ msgid ""
#~ "GrapheneOS is a privacy and security focused mobile OS with Android app\n"
#~ "                    compatibility developed as a non-profit "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "\n"
#~ "                    project. It's focused on the research and development of privacy and security\n"
#~ "                    technology including substantial improvements to sandboxing, exploit\n"
#~ "                    mitigations and the permission model. It was founded in 2014 and was\n"
#~ "                    "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "GrapheneOS improves the privacy and security of the OS from the bottom up.\n"
#~ "                    It deploys technologies to mitigate whole classes of vulnerabilities and make\n"
#~ "                    exploiting the most common sources of vulnerabilities substantially more\n"
#~ "                    difficult. It improves the security of both the OS and the apps running on it.\n"
#~ "                    The app sandbox and other security boundaries are fortified. GrapheneOS tries\n"
#~ "                    to avoid impacting the user experience with the privacy and security features.\n"
#~ "                    Ideally, the features can be designed so that they're always enabled with no\n"
#~ "                    impact on the user experience and no additional complexity like configuration\n"
#~ "                    options. It's not always feasible, and GrapheneOS does add various toggles for\n"
#~ "                    features like the Network permission, Sensors permission, restrictions when\n"
#~ "                    the device is locked (USB-C and pogo pins, camera, quick tiles), etc. along with\n"
#~ "                    more complex user-facing privacy and security features with their own UX."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " provides an overview of the\n"
#~ "                    substantial privacy and security improvements added by GrapheneOS to the\n"
#~ "                    Android Open Source Project (AOSP). Many of our past features were "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "contributed to AOSP, Linux and other projects to improve\n"
#~ "                    privacy and security for billions of users"
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " so they're no longer listed on\n"
#~ "                    our features page."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "GrapheneOS also develops various apps and services with a focus on privacy\n"
#~ "                    and security. Vanadium is a hardened variant of the Chromium browser and\n"
#~ "                    WebView specifically built for GrapheneOS. GrapheneOS also includes our\n"
#~ "                    minimal security-focused PDF Viewer, our hardware-based Auditor app\n"
#~ "                    providing local and remote verification and attestation of devices,\n"
#~ "                    our modern privacy and security focused camera app, and the externally developed\n"
#~ "                    Seedvault encrypted backup which was initially developed for inclusion in\n"
#~ "                    GrapheneOS."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "GrapheneOS will never include either Google Play services or another\n"
#~ "                    implementation of Google services like microG. It's possible to install Play\n"
#~ "                    services as a set of fully sandboxed apps without special privileges via our\n"
#~ "                    "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " for more\n"
#~ "                    details on our plans for filling in the gaps from not shipping Play services\n"
#~ "                    and Google apps."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "These are all fully supported production-ready targets supporting all the\n"
#~ "                    baseline security features and receiving full monthly security updates\n"
#~ "                    covering all firmware, kernel drivers, driver libraries and services, and other\n"
#~ "                    device-specific code. A fully signed user build for these devices is a proper\n"
#~ "                    GrapheneOS release. Newer generation devices have stronger hardware and firmware\n"
#~ "                    security and hardware-based OS security features and are better development\n"
#~ "                    devices for that reason. It's not possible to work on everything via past\n"
#~ "                    generation devices. The best development devices are Pixels series 8 to 10.\n"
#~ "                    "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "These emulator targets don't receive full monthly security updates, don't\n"
#~ "                    provide all of the baseline security features and are intended for development\n"
#~ "                    usage."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "We recommend using the sdk_phone64_x86_64 target in either the\n"
#~ "                    userdebug or eng variant for most development work."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Providing proper support for a device or generic device family requires\n"
#~ "                    providing an up-to-date kernel and device support code including driver\n"
#~ "                    libraries, firmware and device SELinux policy extensions. Other than some\n"
#~ "                    special cases like the emulator, the generic targets rely on the device support\n"
#~ "                    code present on the device. Shipping all of this is necessary for full security\n"
#~ "                    updates and is tied to enabling verified boot and attestation. Device-specific\n"
#~ "                    driver changes are required to support GrapheneOS features such as the\n"
#~ "                    hardware-level USB-C port control. There's also a lot of device-specific work to\n"
#~ "                    work around or resolve memory corruption bugs uncovered by our features. Most\n"
#~ "                    devices are also missing a lot of standard hardware-based security features we\n"
#~ "                    use such as hardware memory tagging so those features will inherently not be\n"
#~ "                    possible to port to a device not capable of it."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Arch Linux, Debian bookworm, Ubuntu 24.10 and Ubuntu 24.04 LTS are the\n"
#~ "                    officially supported operating systems for building GrapheneOS."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " may not contain directories like\n"
#~ "                        "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ ", and many system administration commands will fail. The\n"
#~ "                        simplest workaround is to add these directories to your "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "\n"
#~ "                        environment variable (and apply the change to your current shell):"
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "136GiB+ storage for a standard sync with history, 90GiB+ storage for a\n"
#~ "                            lightweight sync"
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "32GiB of memory or more. Link-Time Optimization (LTO) creates huge peaks\n"
#~ "                            during linking and is mandatory for Control Flow Integrity (CFI). Linking\n"
#~ "                            Vanadium (Chromium) and the Linux kernel with LTO + CFI are the most memory\n"
#~ "                            demanding tasks."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "100GiB+ of additional free storage space for a typical build of the entire\n"
#~ "                        OS for a multiarch device"
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " as a distribution package or the\n"
#~ "                    self-updating standalone version from the Android Open Source Project. The\n"
#~ "                    self-updating variant avoids dealing with out-of-date distribution packages and\n"
#~ "                    depends on GPG to verify updates."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "The Android Open Source Project build system is designed to provide reliable and\n"
#~ "                    reproducible builds. To accomplish this, it provides a prebuilt toolchain and other\n"
#~ "                    utilities fulfilling most of the build dependency requirements itself. These prebuilt\n"
#~ "                    tools have reproducible builds themselves. It runs the build process within a loose\n"
#~ "                    sandbox to avoid accidental dependencies on the host system. The process of moving to\n"
#~ "                    a fully self-contained build process with minimal external dependencies is gradual and\n"
#~ "                    there are still dependencies that need to be installed on the host system."
