#~ msgid ""
#~ "Web applications must be entirely static HTML/CSS/JavaScript. TypeScript would\n"
#~ "                            make sense at a larger scale but there are no plans for any large web\n"
#~ "                            applications."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid "Rust with "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " for low-level code used in a hypervisor, kernel,\n"
#~ "                            daemon, system library, etc. Keep in mind that low-level code is to be avoided\n"
#~ "                            whenever a higher-level language is better suited to the job. In general,\n"
#~ "                            the project aims to avoid creating more low-level code manually dealing with\n"
#~ "                            memory ownership and lifetimes in the first place."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "C in rare cases for very small and particularly low-level projects without\n"
#~ "                            opportunities to reduce the trusted computing base for memory corruption to\n"
#~ "                            any significant degree with Rust, such as for the hardened_malloc project"
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "arm64 assembly in extremely rare cases where C or Rust aren't usable with\n"
#~ "                            compiler intrinsics"
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Python 3 for small (less than 500 lines) development-related scripts that are\n"
#~ "                            not exposed to untrusted input. It's never acceptable to use it for\n"
#~ "                            client-side code on devices or for servers. It isn't used on the servers even\n"
#~ "                            for non-application-server code."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Bash for tiny (less than 200 lines) build scripts without any non-trivial\n"
#~ "                            logic where Python would be an annoyance."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Much of the work is done on existing projects, and the existing languages should be\n"
#~ "                    used unless there are already clear stable API boundaries where a different language\n"
#~ "                    could be used without causing a substantial maintenance burden. The following\n"
#~ "                    languages are typical from most to least common: Java, C++, C, JavaScript, arm64\n"
#~ "                    assembly, POSIX shell, Bash."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "For existing projects, use the official upstream code style. Avoid using legacy\n"
#~ "                    conventions that they're moving away from themselves. Follow the code style they use\n"
#~ "                    for new additions. Some projects have different code styles for different directories\n"
#~ "                    or files depending on their sources, in which case respect the per-file style."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "For new projects, follow the official code style for the language. Treat the\n"
#~ "                    standard library APIs as defining the naming style for usage of the language, i.e. C\n"
#~ "                    uses "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid " while JavaScript uses "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ ". For Python, follow PEP8 and the\n"
#~ "                    same goes for other languages with official styles whether defined in a document or by\n"
#~ "                    the default mode for the official formatting tool like "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "For cases where there isn't an official or prevailing code style for other things,\n"
#~ "                    avoid tabs, use 4-space indents, "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ ".\n"
#~ "                    Prefer single-line comment syntax other than rare cases where it makes sense to add a\n"
#~ "                    tiny comment within a line of code. In languages with the optional braces misfeature\n"
#~ "                    (C, C++, Java), always use them. Open braces on the same line as function definitions\n"
#~ "                    / statements. Wrap lines at 100 columns except in rare cases where it would be far\n"
#~ "                    uglier to wrap the line."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
