#~ msgid ""
#~ "CSRF mitigation should be implemented via enforcing the presence of\n"
#~ "                    Sec-Fetch-Site with the value same-origin. Services using only POST can also do\n"
#~ "                    this via the more backwards compatible Origin header."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "For web content, use dashes as user-facing word separators rather than underscores.\n"
#~ "                    Page titles should follow the scheme \"Page | Directory | Higher-level directory |\n"
#~ "                    Site\" for usability with a traditional title as the Open Graph title."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid "HTML must pass verification with "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ ".\n"
#~ "                    Ensuring that it parses as XML with "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " catches many common mistakes\n"
#~ "                    and typos that are missed by HTML validation due to the ridiculously permissive nature\n"
#~ "                    of HTML. This enforces closing every tag, using proper escaping and so on. XHTML does\n"
#~ "                    not really exist anymore and we simply use XML parsing as an enforced coding standard\n"
#~ "                    and lint pass. It can also be useful to make it compatible with XML-based tooling."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Avoid designing around class inheritance unless it's a rare case where it's an\n"
#~ "                    extremely good fit or the language sucks (Java) and it's the least bad approach, but\n"
#~ "                    still try to avoid it."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Use concise but self-explanatory variable names. Prefer communicating information\n"
#~ "                    via naming rather than using comments whenever possible. Don't name variables\n"
#~ "                    "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ ", etc. like C programmers. It's okay to\n"
#~ "                    use things like "
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ " for parameters if the function is\n"
#~ "                    genuinely that generic and operates on arbitrary values. In general, try to scope\n"
#~ "                    variables into the most limited scope (in C or C++, be careful about this when\n"
#~ "                    references are taken)."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Write code that's clean and self-explanatory. Use comments to explain or justify\n"
#~ "                    non-obvious things, but try to avoid needing them in the first place. In most cases,\n"
#~ "                    they should just be communicating non-local information such as explaining why an\n"
#~ "                    invariant is true based on the code elsewhere (consider a runtime check to make sure\n"
#~ "                    it's true, or an assertion if performance would be an issue). Docstrings at the top of\n"
#~ "                    top-level functions, modules, etc. are a different story and shouldn't be avoided."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Make extensive usage of well designed standard library modules. For apps, treat\n"
#~ "                    Jetpack (androidx) as part of the standard library and make good use of it. For Java,\n"
#~ "                    Guava can also be treated as part of the standard library."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Libraries outside of the standard library should be used very cautiously. They\n"
#~ "                    should be well maintained, stable, well tested and widely used. Libraries implemented\n"
#~ "                    with memory unsafe languages should generally be avoided (one exception: SQLite)."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Generally, frameworks and libraries existing solely to provide different paradigms\n"
#~ "                    and coding patterns are to be avoided. They increase barrier to entry for developers,\n"
#~ "                    generally only increase complexity unless used at very large scales (and may not even\n"
#~ "                    make things simpler in those cases) and come and go as fads. This is only okay when\n"
#~ "                    it's part of the standard libraries or libraries that are considered standard\n"
#~ "                    (androidx, Guava) by GrapheneOS and should still be approached cautiously. Only use it\n"
#~ "                    if it truly makes the correct approach simpler. Ignore fads and figure out if it\n"
#~ "                    actually makes sense to use, otherwise just stick to the old fashioned way if the\n"
#~ "                    fancy alternatives aren't genuinely better."
#~ msgstr ""

